# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: germany
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] From the 1680s to 1789, Germany comprised many small territories which were parts of the Holy Roman Empire of the German Nation.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Meanwhile, the states developed a classical culture that found its greatest expression in the Enlightenment, with world class leaders such as philosophers Leibniz and Kant, writers such as Goethe and Schiller, and musicians Bach and Beethoven.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Germany, or more exactly the old Holy Roman Empire, in the 18th century entered a period of decline that would finally lead to the dissolution of the Empire during the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Since the Peace of Westphalia in 1648, the Empire had been fragmented into numerous independent states (Kleinstaaterei).
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In 1701, Elector Frederick of Brandenburg was crowned "King *in* Prussia".
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] From 1713 to 1740, King Frederick William I, also known as the "Soldier King", established a highly centralized state.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The term *German dualism* describes the long conflict between the two largest German states Austria and Prussia from 1740 to 1866 when Prussia finally forced Austria out of the German Confederation.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The Kingdom of Prussia emerged as the leading state of the Empire.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Frederick III (1688–1701) became King Frederick I of Prussia in 1701.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Since there was only one King of the Germans within the Empire, Frederick gained the assent of Emperor Leopold I (in return for alliance against France in the War of the Spanish Succession) to his adoption (January 1701) of the title of "King in Prussia" based on his non-imperial territories.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The title came into general acceptance with the Treaty of Utrecht (1713).
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Sweden's defeat by Russia, Saxony, Poland, Denmark–Norway, Hanover, and Prussia in the Great Northern War (1700–21) marked the end of significant Swedish power on the southern shores of the Baltic Sea.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In the Prusso–Swedish Treaty of Stockholm (January 1720), Prussia regained Stettin (Szczecin) and other parts of Sweden's holding in Pomerania.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The Hohenzollerns of Brandenburg had held the reversion to the Duchy of Pomerania since 1472.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] During this time, the trends set in motion by the Great Elector reached their culmination, as the Junkers, the landed aristocracy, were welded to the Prussian Army.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In 1740, King Frederick II (Frederick the Great) came to the throne.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Using the pretext of a 1537 treaty (vetoed by Emperor Ferdinand I), by which parts of Silesia were to pass to Brandenburg after the extinction of its ruling Piast dynasty, Frederick invaded Silesia, thereby beginning the War of the Austrian Succession (1740–48).
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In 1744, Frederick invaded again to forestall reprisals and to claim, this time, the province of Bohemia.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] He failed, but French pressure on Austria's ally Great Britain led to a series of treaties and compromises, culminating in the 1748 Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle that restored peace and left Prussia in possession of most of Silesia.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] When Frederick preemptively invaded Saxony and Bohemia over the course of a few months in 1756–57, he initiated the Seven Years' War.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] This war was a desperate struggle for the Prussian Army, and the fact that it managed to fight much of Europe to a draw bears witness to Frederick's military skills.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The situation became progressively grimmer until the death of Empress Elizabeth of Russia (the miracle of the House of Brandenburg).
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The accession of the Prussophile Peter III relieved the pressure on the eastern front.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Defeating the Austrian army at the Battle of Burkersdorf and relying on continuing British success against France in the war's colonial theatres, Prussia was finally able to force a *status quo ante bellum* on the continent.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] This result confirmed Prussia's major role within the German states and established the country as a European great power.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] This gave the start to the rivalry between Prussia and Austria for the leadership of Germany, referred to as German dualism.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] From 1763, against resistance from the nobility and citizenry, an "enlightened absolutism" was established in Prussia and Austria, according to which the ruler was to be "the first servant of the state".
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The economy developed and legal reforms were undertaken, including the abolition of torture and the improvement in the status of Jews; the emancipation of the peasants began.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In 1772–95, Prussia took part in the partitions of Poland, occupying western territories of the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth, which led to centuries of Polish resistance against German rule and persecution.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] To the east and south of Prussia, the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth had gradually weakened during the 18th century.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Frederick took part in the first of the partitions of Poland, between Russia, Prussia, and Austria in 1772.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The Kingdom of Prussia annexed most of the Polish province of Royal Prussia, including Warmia; the annexed land was organized the following year into the Province of West Prussia.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The new territory connected East Prussia (the territory previously known as the Duchy of Prussia) with Pomerania, uniting the kingdom's eastern territories.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] After Frederick died in 1786, his nephew Fredrick William II continued the partitions, gaining a large part of western Poland in 1793.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In 1795, the Kingdom of Poland ceased to exist and a large area (including Warsaw) to the south of East Prussia became part of Prussia.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] These new territories were organized into the Provinces of New Silesia, South Prussia, and New East Prussia.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The French Revolution sparked a new war between France and several of its Eastern neighbors, including Prussia and Austria.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Following the Peace of Basel in 1795 with Prussia, the west bank of the Rhine was ceded to France.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Napoleon I of France relaunched the war against the Empire.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In 1803, under the *"Reichsdeputationshauptschluss"* (a resolution of a committee of the Eternal Imperial Diet meeting in Regensburg), he abolished almost all the ecclesiastical and the smaller secular states and most of the imperial free cities.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] New medium-sized states were established in south-western Germany.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In turn, Prussia gained territory in north-western Germany.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The Holy Roman Empire was formally dissolved on 6 August 1806 when the last Holy Roman Emperor Francis II (from 1804, Emperor Francis I of Austria) resigned.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Francis II's family continued to be called Austrian emperors until 1918.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In 1806, the Confederation of the Rhine was established under Napoleon's protection.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] From 1640, Brandenburg-Prussia had started to rise under the Great Elector, Frederick William.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The Peace of Westphalia in 1648 strengthened it even further, through the acquisition of East Pomerania.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] From 1713 to 1740, King Frederick William I, also known as the "Soldier King", established a highly centralized, militarized state with a heavily rural population of about three million (compared to the nine million in Austria).
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In terms of the boundaries of 1914, Germany in 1700 had a population of 16 million, increasing slightly to 17 million by 1750, and growing more rapidly to 24 million by 1800.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Wars continued, but they were no longer so devastating to the civilian population; famines and major epidemics did not occur, but increased agricultural productivity led to a higher birth rate, and a lower death rate.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In the War of the Austrian Succession (1740–48) Maria Theresa fought successfully for recognition of her succession to the throne.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] But in the Silesian Wars and in the Seven Years' War she had to cede 95 percent of Silesia to Frederick II, the Great, of Prussia.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] After the Peace of Hubertsburg in 1763 between Austria, Prussia and Saxony, Prussia became a European great power.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] This gave the start to the rivalry between Prussia and Austria for the leadership of Germany.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] From 1763, against resistance from the nobility and citizenry, an "enlightened absolutism" was established in Prussia and Austria, according to which the ruler governed according to the best precepts of the philosophers.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The economies developed and legal reforms were undertaken, including the abolition of torture and the improvement in the status of Jews.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Emancipation of the peasants slowly began.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In 1772–1795 Prussia and Austria took part in the partitions of Poland.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Prussia occupied the western territories of the former Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth that surrounded existing Prussian holdings, while Austria took the territory of Galicia further south.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] This occupation led to centuries of Polish resistance against Germanization.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] To the west of Austria and Prussia stood the remaining, major, part of Germany.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The existence of the two big powers precluded a serious reform of the confederate structure of Germany; but reform of the individual state governments and administrations was not excluded.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The general picture was as varied as the political map of the Holy Roman Empire, and it is difficult to generalise.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] But the impression prevails that, overall, after 1750 and especially after 1770, the general situation of the middle classes improved slightly, both economically and politically.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Reforms were carried in a number of large and small states.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] There were some profligate, vicious and dull-witted rulers, but there were also some outstanding personalities.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The bureaucrats, if often corrupt, were more competent and better educated than before.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Saxony remained in the vanguard of German cultural activities, and its commercial and industrial activities remained considerable; but politically, it was outclassed by its neighbor Brandenburg-Prussia.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Bavaria was especially unfortunate; it was a rural land with very heavy debts and few growth centers.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In Württemberg the duke lavished funds on palaces, mistresses, great celebrations, and hunting expeditions.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Among the smaller princes, many offensive characters could be found, but also many of outstanding figures, such as Duke William Ferdinand of Brunswick and Margrave Karl Friedrich of Baden.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Under the rule of Karl Friedrich, an enthusiast for The Enlightenment, Baden enjoyed some of the best governments of the smaller states.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Serfdom was abolished in 1783, although this was done primarily to avert peasant unrest and the flight of unfree Baden peasants to neighboring Breisgau after Joseph II abolished serfdom in that Austrian province in 1781.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] A large part of Germany still lived under the rule of bishops.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Conditions in these ecclesiastical principalities were no less variegated than those of the secular states.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] All the bishops were scions of the ruling dynasties or the high aristocracy and they considered themselves political rulers who lived and acted in the style of the contemporary secular court society.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Their sense of responsibility and their capacity for the administration of their territories also varied greatly.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] However, even at their best, they could not achieve the continuity of government that some dynastic states began to acquire.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In Hesse-Kassel, the Landgrave Frederick II ruled from 1760 to 1785 as an enlightened despot, and raised money by hiring soldiers (called "Hessians") to Great Britain to help fight the American Revolutionary War.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] He combined Enlightenment ideas with Christian values, cameralist plans for central control of the economy, and a militaristic approach to diplomacy.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Hanover did not have to support a lavish court: its rulers were also kings of England and resided in London.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] George III, elector (ruler) from 1760 to 1820, never once visited Hanover.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The local nobility who ran the country opened the University of Göttingen in 1737; it soon became a world-class intellectual center.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In a heavily agrarian society, land ownership played a central role.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Germany's nobles, especially those in the East – called Junkers –dominated not only the localities, but also the Prussian court, and especially the Prussian army.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Increasingly after 1815, a centralized Prussian government based in Berlin took over the powers of the nobles, which in terms of control over the peasantry had been almost absolute.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] To help the nobility avoid indebtedness, Berlin set up a credit institution to provide capital loans in 1809, and extended the loan network to peasants in 1849.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] When the German Empire was established in 1871, the Junker nobility controlled the army and the Navy, the bureaucracy, and the royal court; they generally set governmental policies.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Peasants continued to center their lives on the village, where they were members of a corporate body and helped manage the community resources and monitor the community life.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In the East, they were serfs who were bound permanently to parcels of land.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In most of Germany, farming was undertaken by tenant farmers who paid rents and carried out obligatory services to the landlord, who was typically a nobleman.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Peasant leaders supervised the fields and ditches and grazing rights, maintained public order and morals, and supported a village court which handled minor offenses.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Within the family the patriarch made all the decisions, and tried to arrange advantageous marriages for his children.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Much of the villages' communal life centered around church services and holy days.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In Prussia, the peasants drew lots to choose conscripts required by the army.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The noblemen handled external relationships and politics for the villages under their control, and were not typically involved in daily activities or decisions.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In German history the emancipation of the serfs came between 1770 and 1830, with the nobility in Schleswig being the first to agree to do so in 1797, followed by the signing of the royal and political leaders of Denmark and Germany in 1804.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The peasants, no longer serfs, could own their land, buy and sell it, and move about freely.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The nobles approved; for now they could buy land owned by the peasants.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The chief reformer was Baron vom Stein(1757–1831), who was influenced by The Enlightenment, especially the free market ideas of Adam Smith.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The end of serfdom raised the personal legal status of the peasantry.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] A bank was set up so that landowner could borrow government money to buy land from peasants (the peasants were not allowed to use it to borrow money to buy land until 1850).
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The result was that the large landowners obtained larger estates, and many peasants became landless tenants, or moved to the cities or to America.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The other German states imitated Prussia after 1815.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In sharp contrast to the violent events of the French Revolution, Germany handled land reform peacefully.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In Schleswig the peasants, who had been influenced by the Enlightenment, played an active role; elsewhere they were largely passive.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Indeed, for most peasants, customs and traditions continued largely unchanged, including the old habits of deference to the nobles whose legal authority over the villagers remained quite strong.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Although the peasants were no longer tied to the land, the old paternalistic relationship in East Prussia lasted into the 20th century.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The agrarian reforms in northwestern Germany in 1770–1870 were driven by progressive governments and local elites.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] They abolished feudal obligations and divided collectively owned common land into private parcels; and thus created a more efficient market-oriented rural economy; resulting in higher productivity and population growth.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] It strengthened the traditional social order because wealthy peasants obtained most of the former common land, while the rural proletariat was left without land; many left for the cities or America.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Meanwhile, the division of the common land served as a buffer preserving social peace between nobles and peasants.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In the east the serfs were emancipated but the Junker class maintained its large estates and monopolized political power.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Around 1800 the Catholic monasteries, which had large land holdings, were nationalized and sold off by the government.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In Bavaria they had controlled 56% of the land.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Before 1750, the German upper classes often looked to France (or, previously, Italy) for intellectual, cultural and architectural leadership; French was the language of high society.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] By the mid-18th century the "Aufklärung" (The Enlightenment) had transformed German high culture in music, philosophy, science and literature.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Christian Wolff (1679–1754) was the pioneer as a writer who expounded the Enlightenment to German readers; he legitimized German as a philosophic language.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Johann Gottfried Herder (1744–1803) broke new ground in philosophy and poetry, as a leader of the Sturm und Drang movement of proto-Romanticism.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Weimar Classicism ("Weimarer Klassik") was a cultural and literary movement based in Weimar that sought to establish a new humanism by synthesizing Romantic, classical, and Enlightenment ideas.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The movement, from 1772 until 1805, involved Herder as well as polymath Johann Wolfgang von Goethe (1749–1832) and Friedrich Schiller (1759–1805), a poet and historian.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Herder argued that every folk had its own particular identity, which was expressed in its language and culture.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] This legitimized the promotion of German language and culture and helped shape the development of German nationalism.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Schiller's plays expressed the restless spirit of his generation, depicting the hero's struggle against social pressures and the force of destiny.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] German music, sponsored by the upper classes, came of age under composers Johann Sebastian Bach (1685–1750), Joseph Haydn (1732–1809), Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart (1756–1791), and Ludwig van Beethoven.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In remote Königsberg philosopher Immanuel Kant (1724–1804) tried to reconcile rationalism and religious belief, individual freedom, and political authority.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Kant's work contained basic tensions that would continue to shape German thought – and indeed all of European philosophy – well into the 20th century.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The German Enlightenment won the support of princes, aristocrats, and the middle classes, and it permanently reshaped the culture.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] German reaction to the French Revolution was mixed at first.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] German intellectuals celebrated the outbreak, hoping to see the triumph of Reason and The Enlightenment.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The royal courts in Vienna and Berlin denounced the overthrow of the king and the threatened spread of notions of liberty, equality, and fraternity.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] By 1793, the execution of the French king and the onset of the Terror disillusioned the Bildungsbürgertum (educated middle classes).
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Reformers said the solution was to have faith in the ability of Germans to reform their laws and institutions in peaceful fashion.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Europe was racked by two decades of war revolving around France's efforts to spread its revolutionary ideals, as well as to annex Belgium and the Rhine's Left Bank to France and establish puppet regimes in the Netherlands, Germany and Italy.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The French revolutionaries' open and strident republicanism led to the conclusion of a defensive alliance between Austria and Prussia on 7 February 1792.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The alliance also declared that any violation of the borders of the Empire by France would be a cause for war.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The extremists among the French revolutionaries saw war as a chance to defeat their domestic opponents and embarrass the king, whose Austrian wife, Marie-Antoinette, was Emperor Leopold II's sister.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] They demanded that Austria not only disarm but abandon all alliances directed against France.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Upon Leopold II's refusal, France declared war on Austria and Prussia on 20 April.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Austria and Prussia then invaded France, but were defeated at the Battle of Valmy (1792).
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The German lands saw armies marching back and forth, bringing devastation (albeit on a far lower scale than the Thirty Years' War, almost two centuries before), but also bringing new ideas of liberty and civil rights for the people.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Prussia and Austria ended their failed wars with France but (with Russia) partitioned Poland among themselves in 1793 and 1795.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The French took control of the Rhineland, imposed French-style reforms, abolished feudalism, established constitutions, promoted freedom of religion, emancipated Jews, opened the bureaucracy to ordinary citizens of talent, and forced the nobility to share power with the rising middle class.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Napoleon created the Kingdom of Westphalia (1807–1813) as a model state.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] These reforms proved largely permanent and modernized the western parts of Germany.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] When the French tried to impose the French language, German opposition grew in intensity.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] A Second Coalition of Britain, Russia, and Austria then attacked France but failed.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Napoleon established direct or indirect control over most of western Europe, including the German states apart from Prussia and Austria.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] The old Holy Roman Empire was little more than a farce; Napoleon simply abolished it in 1806 while forming new countries under his control.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] In Germany Napoleon set up the "Confederation of the Rhine", comprising most of the German states except Prussia and Austria.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Prussia tried to remain neutral while imposing tight controls on dissent, but with German nationalism sharply on the rise, the small nation blundered by going to war with Napoleon in 1806.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Its economy was weak, its leadership poor, and the once mighty Prussian army was a hollow shell.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Napoleon easily crushed it at the Battle of Jena (1806).
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Napoleon occupied Berlin, and Prussia paid dearly.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Prussia lost its recently acquired territories in western Germany, its army was reduced to 42,000 men, no trade with Britain was allowed, and Berlin had to pay Paris heavy reparations and fund the French army of occupation.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Saxony changed sides to support Napoleon and join his Confederation of the Rhine; its elector was rewarded with the title of king and given a slice of Poland taken from Prussia.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] After Napoleon's failed invasion of Russia in 1812, including the deaths of many Germans in his invasion army, Prussia joined with Russia.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Major battles followed in quick order, and when Austria switched sides to oppose Napoleon his situation grew tenuous.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] He was defeated at the Battle of Leipzig in late 1813, and his empire quickly unraveled.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] One after another the German states switched to oppose Napoleon, but he rejected peace terms.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Allied armies invaded France in early 1814, Paris fell, and in April Napoleon surrendered.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] He returned for 100 days in 1815, but was finally defeated by the British and German armies at Waterloo.
[src:germany/18th-century-history-of-germany] Prussia was the big winner at the Vienna peace conference, gaining extensive territory.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] A referendum on withdrawing from the League of Nations was held in Germany on 12 November 1933 alongside Reichstag elections.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] The measure was approved by 95% of voters with a turnout of 96%.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] It was the first of a series of referendums held by the German cabinet under Chancellor Adolf Hitler, after the cabinet conferred upon itself the ability to hold referendums on 14 July 1933.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] The referendum question was on a separate ballot from the one used for the elections.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] Weimar President Paul von Hindenburg appointed Adolf Hitler to the office of Chancellor on 30 January 1933.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] Hitler wanted the Reichstag to pass an "enabling act" to allow his government to promulgate laws directly, without going through the Reichstag.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] Lacking the two-thirds supermajority necessary to pass such a constitutional reform, he had Hindenburg dissolve the Reichstag on 31 January.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] In the resulting election on 5 March, the Nazis surged to 43.9% of the vote.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] Including his allies, Hitler had 60% of the deputies, but needed the support of the Catholic Centre Party to reach the supermajority.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] After securing their support by promising to respect the rights of the Catholic Church, the Enabling Act of 1933 passed 441–94 (107 left-wing deputies were arrested or fleeing) on 23 March.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] Hitler had become a dictator, with Hindenburg technically retaining the ability to dismiss Hitler.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] The Weimar Constitution allowed the President to refer legislation passed by the Reichstag to a referendum.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] A referendum would also be held if 10% of eligible voters proposed an initiative.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] On 14 July 1933, the German cabinet used the Enabling Act to pass the "Law concerning the Plebiscite", which permitted the cabinet to call a referendum on "questions of national policy" and "laws which the cabinet had enacted".
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] While the Weimar provisions allowing for referendums were not explicitly repealed, subsequent legislation made it clear those provisions would not be used.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] To whip up nationalist sentiment in the run up to the vote, the Nazi Party intentionally timed the referendum to take place as close as possible to the fifteenth anniversary of the Armistice of Compiègne, then a bitter memory in the minds of the Nazis and most ordinary Germans.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] Since German elections always took place on Sundays, the vote was held one day after the anniversary.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] Of the democratic nature of the referendum, the political scientist Arnold Zurcher writes that "there undoubtedly was a great deal" of "intangible official pressure" but probably very little "downright coercion and intimidation at the polls".
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] The historian Heinrich August Winkler notes that "the rejection of the Versailles system was extraordinarily popular" and that at this stage in the history of Nazi Germany, it was still possible to vote negatively, to invalidate one's ballot or not to vote at all "without great personal risk".
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] In particular, the Nazis made no effort to prevent the casting of negative or invalid votes in districts that were known to have large populations of Jews, Poles and other ethnic minorities, who were then still allowed to vote.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] The expected unfavourable results in such areas would be useful in propaganda as proof of disloyalty to the Reich.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] In East Prussia, the stronghold of the *Junker*, support for withdrawal reached 97%, while in Hamburg, formerly a communist stronghold, only 84% voted in favour.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] This regional variation was repeated in the referendum of 1934.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] In general, rural parts of the country were more favourable and the cities least favourable to withdrawal, but overall support was higher than for granting Hitler presidential powers in 1934.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] Voter turnout was greatest in the Pfalz region, where 98.4% of registered voters cast ballots.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] It was lowest in the affluent Berlin suburb of Potsdam at 90%.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] At a Berlin Jewish hospital there were 122 votes cast, with 101 for "Yes", 12 for "No" and 9 invalid.
[src:germany/1933-german-referendum] In the Osthofen concentration camp there were 79 "Yes" votes of 88 entitled to vote, at the Brandenburg concentration camp 1,024 "Yes" votes and 12 "No" votes, and in the Oranienburg concentration camp 330 "Yes" votes and 33 "No".
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The **1936 Summer Olympics** (German: *Olympische Sommerspiele 1936*), officially the **Games of the XI Olympiad** (German: *Spiele der XI.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Olympiade*) and branded as **Berlin 1936**, were an international multi-sport event held from 1 to 16 August 1936 in Berlin, Germany.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Berlin won the right to host the Games over Barcelona at the 29th IOC Session in 1931.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The 1936 Games were the second and last occasion on which the International Olympic Committee (IOC) chose a host by a ballot in which the bidding cities themselves could vote; later rules barred cities that hosted the vote from being selected.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Games had been awarded to Germany during the Weimar Republic, but by 1936 the country was governed by the Nazi regime, and Adolf Hitler's government treated the Olympics as an opportunity for propaganda.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] To project an image of a peaceful, tolerant Germany, the authorities temporarily removed antisemitic signage and softened the most visible forms of persecution for the duration of the Games.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] At the same time, the German Olympic authorities barred nearly all Jewish and Romani athletes from the national team; the fencer Helene Mayer, who had one Jewish parent, was the only such athlete to represent Germany.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] A movement to boycott or relocate the Games developed in several countries—Czechoslovakia, France, the Netherlands, Sweden, the United Kingdom, and the United States—but it ultimately failed.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Forty-nine nations competed, the largest number at any Olympics to that point.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] These were the first Games to be televised and the first to feature a torch relay carrying the Olympic flame from Olympia to the host city—a ceremony devised for Berlin that became a permanent Olympic tradition.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The filmmaker Leni Riefenstahl recorded the Games for her two-part film *Olympia*, which pioneered techniques still used in sports cinematography.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Jesse Owens of the United States won four gold medals in the sprint and long jump events, and became the most successful athlete to compete in Berlin, while Germany was the most successful country overall with 101 medals (38 of them gold); the United States placed a distant second with 57 medals.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] These were the final Olympic Games under the IOC presidency of Henri de Baillet-Latour.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] For the next 12 years, no Olympic Games were held due to the immense world disruption caused by the Second World War.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The next Olympic Games were held in 1948 (the Winter Games in St.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Moritz, Switzerland, and then the Summer Games in London, England).
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] At the 28th IOC Session in Berlin in May 1930, fourteen cities indicated an intention to bid for the 1936 Summer Olympics.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] By the 29th Session, held in Barcelona in April 1931, only Barcelona and Berlin remained in contention; the other cities—Alexandria, Budapest, Buenos Aires, Cologne, Dublin, Frankfurt, Helsinki, Lausanne, Montevideo, Nuremberg, Rio de Janeiro, and Rome—had withdrawn.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Several of these cities later hosted the Games: Helsinki in 1952, Rome in 1960, Barcelona in 1992 and Rio de Janeiro in 2016.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The 1936 Games were the first for which the host was decided by a vote of each individual IOC member rather than by the assembled Session alone.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The deadline for ballots was 13 May 1931, two weeks after the Barcelona Session.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Of 67 voting members, 19 cast ballots during the Session and 40 by post to the IOC headquarters in Lausanne; eight abstained.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The result was 43 votes for Berlin and 16 for Barcelona.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Barcelona's prospects were probably weakened by the political uncertainty that followed the proclamation of the Second Spanish Republic days before the Session.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] After the Nazi seizure of power in 1933 and the regime's early antisemitic measures, some IOC members privately discussed moving the Games, and the US Olympic Association briefly suggested transferring them to Rome.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler's government gave assurances that Jewish athletes would not be excluded from the German team, and the proposal was not seriously pursued.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Awarded to Berlin in 1931 under the Weimar Republic, the Games took on a new character after the Nazi takeover of January 1933, as the regime grasped their value as international propaganda.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler regarded the Games as a chance to promote his government and its ideology of Aryan supremacy.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The official Nazi paper, the *Völkischer Beobachter*, had argued in the strongest terms that Jewish and black athletes should be barred from the Olympics.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] As the Games approached, however, the regime worked to soften Germany's international image: signs reading "Jews not welcome" (German: *Juden unerwünscht*) were taken down from public places for the duration, and overt antisemitic agitation was muted.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The effort extended to the removal of people the regime considered undesirable.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] In July 1936 the Ministry of the Interior authorised Berlin's police to detain the city's Romani and confine them in a special camp at Marzahn, on the city's outskirts.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Five months before the opening ceremony, in March 1936, Germany had remilitarised the Rhineland in breach of the Treaty of Versailles, heightening international tension in the months before the Games.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] In line with Nazi directives, the German Olympic Committee effectively barred German athletes who were Jewish or Roma, or of such ancestry, from competing.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The most prominent excluded athlete was the high jumper Gretel Bergmann, who was dropped from the team shortly after equalling the German record of 1.60 m in June 1936.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Others kept off the team included the record-holding track-and-field athlete Lilli Henoch, the tennis player Daniel Prenn, the boxer Erich Seelig and the Sinti boxer Johann Trollmann.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Helene Mayer—already an Olympic champion who had emigrated to the United States—returned to fence for Germany and won a silver medal, the only athlete of Jewish descent on the German team, a token inclusion intended to deflect foreign criticism.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The exclusions also reached the organisers.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Although the Olympic flame had been reintroduced at the 1928 Summer Olympics, Berlin staged the first torch relay, carrying a flame kindled at Olympia in Greece to the host city through seven countries.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The concept, organised by Diem, established the modern convention later used at every Games, and Riefenstahl incorporated the relay into *Olympia*.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Olympic Village lay at Elstal in Wustermark, about 30 km west of central Berlin, and comprised low dormitories, a large "Dining Hall of the Nations", training facilities and a swimming hall.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] After the Games the site was absorbed by the Wehrmacht and later used by Soviet forces as a military camp; parts of it, including the dormitory used by Jesse Owens, have been restored more recently.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Twenty-two venues were used, most of them in the purpose-built Reichssportfeld complex, which had been planned for the cancelled 1916 Summer Olympics and was completed in 1934–36.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The centrepiece Olympic Stadium seated about 100,000; sailing was held in the Bay of Kiel, later reused for the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Games were the first to be carried on live television.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Using Telefunken equipment, the German Post Office transmitted more than 70 hours of black-and-white coverage to public viewing rooms in Berlin and Potsdam, where more than 162,000 people in all followed the competitions on screens outside the stadium.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Radio carried the Games more widely still, in 28 languages across some 2,500 broadcasts.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Games were also an early showcase for colour photography, using Germany's newly developed Agfacolor film.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The filmmaker Leni Riefenstahl recorded the Games for her two-part documentary *Olympia*, released in 1938.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Games were among the most lavish staged to that point, and most of the spending lay well outside the organising committee's own accounts.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The organisers had originally budgeted the Games at about 4 million Reichsmark, to be raised through a three-year Olympic lottery, surcharged Olympic postage stamps and an "Olympic Penny" added to admission tickets at sporting events across Germany.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The stamps alone had been forecast to raise one million Reichsmark; in the event they brought in considerably more.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] From 1933 the Reich Ministry of the Interior directed a vast building programme that the regime folded into its public-works and job-creation schemes, and historians have treated this state investment—rather than ticket income—as the truer measure of what the Games cost.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Its centrepiece, the new Olympic Stadium, was built in barely two years at a cost of around 42 million Reichsmark; with the wider Reichssportfeld, the Olympic Village and new transport links, the state's outlay dwarfed the committee's budget.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler also prized the Games as a way to earn scarce foreign currency at a time of dwindling German reserves, later claiming they had brought in large sums.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The committee's own books were comparatively modest: ticket sales brought in about 7.5 million RM and an operating profit of over one million RM.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The city of Berlin reported costs of about 16.5 million RM, while the national government's total spending was never published in full and has been estimated at around US$30 million.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Games also attracted commercial advertising: Coca-Cola's German subsidiary supplied the drink and promoted it heavily in Berlin during the Games, and the company's own account of its Olympic partnerships lists it as a sponsor of the 1936 Games.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Berlin confectioner Hildebrand introduced its caffeinated chocolate Scho-Ka-Kola at the Games, marketing it as a "sport chocolate" (German: *Sportschokolade*).
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Winter Games at Garmisch-Partenkirchen earlier that year had featured some of the first official commercial arrangements at an Olympics, with Coca-Cola acting as a sponsor and Ovaltine designated the "official drink".
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The sporting programme ran from 1 to 16 August 1936 and was framed by elaborate opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony took place at the Olympic Stadium on 1 August 1936.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The airship *Hindenburg* flew over the stadium trailing the Olympic flag.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] After Hitler's arrival the parade of nations proceeded, with Greece first and the host nation last; some teams gave the Nazi salute or the similar Olympic salute as they passed Hitler's box, with French Olympians giving a Roman salute, while the United States and a few others did not.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Greek team that led the parade was headed by Spyridon Louis, winner of the marathon at the first modern Olympics in 1896, who presented Hitler with an olive branch from Olympia.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler then declared the Games open; in keeping with Olympic protocol his part was confined to the set formula—"I proclaim the Games of Berlin, celebrating the eleventh Olympiad of the modern era, to be open"—his only public statement during the Games.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] A torch-bearer then ran into the arena to light the cauldron, and thousands of pigeons were released.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] During the ceremony the Olympic Hymn—specially composed by Richard Strauss, who conducted it himself—received its première; Strauss had taken the commission only after the writer Gerhart Hauptmann failed to supply a text, and he privately dismissed the piece even as he led it.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The programme comprised 129 events in 25 disciplines across 19 sports.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Basketball, canoeing and handball made their Olympic debuts; handball would not return until the 1972 Summer Olympics, while polo made its fifth and final Olympic appearance.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Baseball and gliding were held as demonstration sports, and art competitions awarded medals, as did feats of alpinism and aeronautics recognised at the closing ceremony.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] National strengths were pronounced across the individual sports.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The host nation owed its place atop the medal table chiefly to gymnastics, rowing and the equestrian events, in which German riders won all six golds.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Athletics, the largest sport, was dominated by the United States, whose men won twelve track-and-field golds; Helen Stephens took two of the six women's events.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] In the pool the men's programme became a duel between the US and Japan, while Rie Mastenbroek of the Netherlands, the outstanding swimmer of the Games, led Dutch dominance of the women's events; US women instead won both diving titles.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] France's Robert Charpentier won three cycling golds, and the fencing titles fell mainly to Italy and Hungary.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The team events produced their own milestones.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The United States won the first Olympic basketball tournament, beating Canada 19–8 in a final played outdoors on a rain-soaked clay court, with the game's inventor James Naismith on hand to present the medals.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Germany won the inaugural field handball competition, an eleven-a-side outdoor game, and Hungary took the water polo, a sport it would go on to dominate.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Italy won the football and India a third successive hockey gold, while polo, won by Argentina, was contested for the last time.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The outstanding individual performer was Jesse Owens of the United States, who won gold in the 100 m, 200 m, long jump, and 4×100 m relay.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] In the long jump his German rival Luz Long offered him advice after he nearly failed to qualify, and the two were publicly cordial.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Mack Robinson, brother of Jackie Robinson, took 200 m silver behind Owens.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] In the 800 m, John Woodruff won gold after deliberately slowing to free himself when boxed in.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Jack Lovelock of New Zealand won the 1500 m in a world-record 3:47.8.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] In the decathlon, Glenn Morris of the United States set a world record of 7,900 points to lead an American medal sweep, and Ondina Valla took the 80 m hurdles to become the first Italian woman to win an Olympic title, in a final so close that the first four finishers were given the same time.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] German athletes were strong in several sports, sweeping all six equestrian golds and, in the gymnasts Konrad Frey and Alfred Schwarzmann, producing two triple gold medallists.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The equestrian team eventing title owed much to Konrad von Wangenheim, who finished the cross-country phase despite breaking his collarbone in a fall and returned the next day—his arm in a sling—to complete the jumping after he and his horse fell again.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Rie Mastenbroek of the Netherlands won three swimming golds and a silver, and the Estonian Kristjan Palusalu became the only wrestler to win both the freestyle and Greco-Roman heavyweight titles at a single Games.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Egyptian weightlifter Khadr El Touni won the middleweight gold with a world-record total, beating the German silver medallist by a wide margin.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] In the football tournament, Italy—coached by Vittorio Pozzo between their two FIFA World Cup wins—took gold; the result was claimed by supporters of Benito Mussolini as a vindication of fascism.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Peru had beaten Austria 4–2 after extra time amid a disputed pitch invasion, but the IOC ordered a replay behind closed doors; Peru refused and withdrew from the Games, as did Colombia in sympathy.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] On its Olympic football debut, Japan came from two goals down to beat the favoured Swedes 3–2 before being eliminated by Italy in the next round.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] India won its third consecutive hockey gold, defeating Germany 8–1 in the final.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] In the marathon, the Korean runners Sohn Kee-chung and Nam Sung-yong won gold and bronze while competing for Japan, which then ruled Korea.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] More than half a century later, Sohn carried the Olympic flame into the stadium at the 1988 Summer Olympics in Seoul.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The United States eight, from the University of Washington, won the rowing title with a come-from-behind final, later recounted in *The Boys in the Boat*.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The 13-year-old US Marjorie Gestring won the 3 m springboard, and Betty Robinson, the 1928 100 m champion who had nearly died in a 1931 plane crash, returned to win gold in the 4×100 m relay.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The American Jewish sprinters Marty Glickman and Sam Stoller were dropped from the 4×100 m relay on the morning of the race in favour of Owens and Ralph Metcalfe; the decision has been widely attributed to a wish not to embarrass the German hosts, though the reasons remain disputed.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Games closed on the evening of 16 August 1936 before a crowd of more than 100,000 in the Olympic Stadium.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Historians have described the closing as more sombre and militaristic than the opening, marked by columns of soldiers and fireworks.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] As the ceremony reached its climax, searchlights ringed the arena to form a "dome of light" overhead, the five-ringed Olympic flag was slowly lowered, and the flame that had burned since 1 August was extinguished as the spectators joined in a closing choral hymn.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] IOC president Henri de Baillet-Latour formally declared the Games closed.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] These were the last Olympics of his presidency and, as it proved, the last for twelve years; the 1940 Games had already been awarded to Tokyo at the IOC session held in Berlin on 31 July 1936, before the Olympics even opened.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Two unusual special awards were also recognised in connection with the closing.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] An Olympic gold for alpinism went to the mountaineers Günter and Hettie Dyhrenfurth for their Himalayan expeditions, and the only Olympic gold ever awarded for aeronautics went to the Swiss pilot Hermann Schreiber for the first glider flight across the Alps; neither prize was contested again.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Forty-nine nations competed, up from 37 in 1932.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Five made their first Olympic appearance: Afghanistan, Bermuda, Bolivia, Costa Rica and Liechtenstein.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Several nations returned after missing 1932, while Ireland and Spain competed in 1932 but were absent from Berlin.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Sources give the number of participants differently, largely because of how the art competitions are counted.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives the figure of 3,963 athletes—3,632 men and 331 women—in the sporting events.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The twelve nations that won the most medals at the 1936 Games.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] As at every Games from 1912 to 1948, medals were also awarded in art competitions for works inspired by sport.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The 1936 edition was the largest the Olympics ever staged, with fifteen events across five categories—architecture, literature, music, painting and sculpture—and the entries were shown in an exhibition on the Kaiserdamm that drew some 70,000 visitors.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] A novelty that year was that the prize-winning musical works were performed: the German composer Werner Egk took the orchestral gold for his *Olympic Festive Music*.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] With many French and British artists staying away, German entrants dominated, winning twelve of the thirty-two medals and five of the nine golds; the judges withheld medals entirely in three events.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The art competitions were dropped after 1948; the IOC's currently recognizes them as official and its database give Germany a combined total of 101 medals for the 1936 Games, which includes 12 medals won in art competitions.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Prior to and during the Games, there was considerable debate outside Germany over whether the competition should be allowed or discontinued.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] A number of campaigns to boycott or relocate the Games emerged in the United Kingdom, France, Sweden, Czechoslovakia, the Netherlands, and the United States.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The most consequential debate took place in the United States.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The protests were ultimately unsuccessful; forty-nine teams from around the world participated in the 1936 Games, the largest number of participating nations of any Olympics to that point.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Traditionally, the US sent one of the largest teams to the Olympics, and there was a considerable debate over whether the nation should participate in the 1936 Games.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Americans Milton Green and Norman Cahners refused to attend, and American Jewish organizations, such as the American Jewish Congress and the Jewish Labor Committee, supported a boycott.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Mahoney, president of the Amateur Athletic Union (AAU), contested that racial discrimination was a violation of Olympic rules and that participation in the Games was amount to an indirect endorsement of the Third Reich.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Avery Brundage, then of the American Olympic Committee, opposed the boycott, maintaining that politics had no place in sport and that the Olympic movement would be undermined if nations restricted participation by race or creed.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Most African-American newspapers supported participation in the Olympics.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Philadelphia *Tribune* and the *Chicago Defender* both agreed that black victories would undermine Nazi views of Aryan supremacy and spark renewed African-American pride.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Eventually, Brundage won the debate, convincing the Amateur Athletic Union to close a vote in favor of sending an American team to the Berlin Olympics.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Mahoney's efforts to incite a boycott of the Olympic games in the United States failed, although some athletes like Harvard University track star Milton Green chose to sit at home.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] US President Franklin Roosevelt and his administration did not become involved in the debate, due to a tradition of allowing the Olympic Committee to operate independently of government influence.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Several American diplomats including William E.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Dodd, the American ambassador to Berlin, and George Messersmith, head of the US legation in Vienna, opposed the decision to participate in the games.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Jewish Labour Committee staged a "World Labour Athletic Carnival" in New York during as an alternative sporting event.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Spanish government led by the newly elected left-wing Popular Front boycotted the Games and the Government of Catalonia organized the People's Olympiad as a parallel event in Barcelona.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Some 6,000 athletes from 49 countries registered.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] However, the People's Olympiad was aborted because of the outbreak of the Spanish Civil War just one day before the event was due to start.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union had not participated in international sporting events since the 1920 Summer Olympics.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Soviet government was not invited to the 1920 Games, with the Russian Civil War still raging, and they did not participate in the 1924 Summer Olympics and forward on ideological grounds.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Instead, through the auspices of the Red Sport International, it had participated in a left-wing workers' alternative, the Spartakiad, since 1928.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The USSR had intended to attend the People's Olympiad in Barcelona until it was cancelled; the Soviets did attend the Spartakiad-sponsored 1937 Workers' Summer Olympiad in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union started competing in the Olympics in 1952, when Joseph Stalin realized that they could use the event to fulfil their political and ideological agenda.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] In France, the Jewish fencer Albert Wolff qualified for the national team but withdrew on principle.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Maccabi World Union declined an invitation on behalf of Mandatory Palestine, and two Turkish fencers, Halet Çambel and Suat Fetgeri Aşani—among the first Muslim women to compete at the Olympics—reportedly refused an introduction to Hitler.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Historians widely regard the Berlin Games as a major propaganda success for the Nazi regime, though they differ over how far that success reached.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The US Holocaust Memorial Museum describes them as "a resounding propaganda success" that projected an image of a peaceful, tolerant Germany, and notes that the forty-nine nations who took part lent the regime legitimacy in the eyes of both foreign and domestic audiences.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Most contemporary press coverage was favourable; US newspapers echoed a *New York Times* report that the Games had put Germany "back in the fold of nations".
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Astute diplomats and correspondents stationed in Germany were less easily fooled, but many ordinary visitors and much of the foreign media came away impressed.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Mandell, in the first major English-language study, *The Nazi Olympics* (1971), argued that the regime's unprecedented mass pageantry overwhelmed the critical judgement of visiting journalists, businessmen and diplomats.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Other historians stress that the result turned on the failure of the boycott movement and on the willingness of officials to accept the regime's assurances, rather than on propaganda alone.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Owens's four gold medals became the most enduring popular memory of the Games and were widely seen as a rebuke to Nazi racial theory, though Germany still finished well clear at the top of the medal table.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Owens said he had been treated cordially in Germany and reserved his bitterness for the segregation he faced on returning home, noting that President Franklin Roosevelt neither received nor congratulated him.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The image of a tolerant Germany did not outlast the Games.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Once the foreign visitors had left, anti-Jewish measures resumed and persecution intensified, leading to the Kristallnacht pogrom of November 1938 and, in September 1939, the outbreak of the Second World War.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Several 1936 Olympians were later murdered in the Holocaust, among them the Polish competitors Roman Kantor and Ilia Szrajbman, both killed at Majdanek.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The war forced the cancellation of the 1940 and 1944 Games, and the Olympics did not resume until London 1948.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Games left a lasting cultural and sporting imprint.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Leni Riefenstahl's film *Olympia* (1938) is regarded both as a landmark in cinema—for innovations such as underwater and slow-motion photography that influenced later sports filmmaking—and as a work of state propaganda.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The torch relay and the live television coverage introduced in Berlin became permanent features of the modern Games, and the Olympic Stadium survived the war to be renovated for the 2006 FIFA World Cup final.
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] Owens's story has since been dramatised on film, including in *Race* (2016).
[src:germany/1936-summer-olympics] The Berlin Games are now widely cited as the archetypal example of "sportswashing"—the use of a prestigious sporting event to improve the image of an authoritarian government—and as a precedent in debates over later host selections.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] The **1936 Winter Olympics**, officially the **IV Olympic Winter Games** (German: *IV.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Olympische Winterspiele*) and commonly known as **Garmisch-Partenkirchen 1936**, were a winter multi-sport event held from 6 to 16 February 1936 in Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] They were the fourth edition of the Winter Olympic Games and the first to be held in Germany.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Later the same year the country also hosted the 1936 Summer Olympics in Berlin; 1936 was the last year in which one nation staged both the Summer and Winter Games.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] The Games were organised on behalf of the German League of the Reich for Physical Exercise by Karl Ritter von Halt.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Staged in a Germany governed by the Nazi Party, they prompted international boycott efforts; the regime temporarily removed antisemitic signage and, under outside pressure, allowed the Jewish ice hockey player Rudi Ball to compete for Germany.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Within weeks of the closing ceremony, German forces remilitarized the Rhineland.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] A then-record 28 nations and 646 athletes took part.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] They contested 17 events across four sports, with alpine skiing making its Olympic debut.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Norway led the medal table with seven gold medals.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Among the standout performers were Norway's Ivar Ballangrud, who won three of the four speed-skating titles, and figure skater Sonja Henie, who took her third consecutive Olympic gold, while Great Britain upset defending champions Canada to win the ice hockey tournament.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] At its 29th Session in Barcelona in 1931, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) awarded the 1936 Summer Olympics to Berlin.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Under the rules then in force, the country hosting the Summer Games was also expected, where possible, to stage the Winter Games earlier in the same year.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] The Bavarian towns of Garmisch and Partenkirchen, at the foot of the Zugspitze, were put forward as hosts, and the choice was confirmed by the IOC at its 31st Session in Vienna on 7 June 1933.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Adolf Hitler had become German chancellor in January that year.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] In preparation for the Games, the two towns were merged into a single municipality, Garmisch-Partenkirchen, on 1 January 1935.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] The Games were organised by Karl Ritter von Halt, who had been appointed head of the organising committee by Reichssportführer Hans von Tschammer und Osten.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] According to historians Arnd Krüger and William Murray, Nazi interest in winter sport was encouraged in part by its promotion in Mussolini's Italy, where skiing had been marketed to the middle class.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Because the Games were held in a state governed by the openly antisemitic Nazi regime, several countries debated boycotting both the Winter and Summer Olympics, and some Jewish athletes faced pressure not to take part.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Before foreign visitors arrived, the authorities temporarily removed antisemitic signs from the host towns and—under pressure linked to a possible American boycott—allowed Rudi Ball, the only Jewish athlete on the German team, to play in the ice hockey tournament.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Shortly before the opening, IOC president Henri de Baillet-Latour reminded Hitler that the Games were to be kept free of political propaganda and conducted under the IOC's rules.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] No nation boycotted the Winter Games, and the 28 that competed were the most at any Winter Olympics up to that point.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] The competition passed with little overt political controversy, although the Canadian team's raised-arm "Olympic salute" during the opening ceremony was mistaken by spectators for the Nazi salute.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] The Große Olympiaschanze ski jump was built for the Games, and the adjoining ski stadium staged the opening and closing ceremonies, the cross-country races and the ski-jumping events.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] A financial statement compiled in April 1936 showed that both spending and income had more than doubled the organising committee's original 1933 estimates of around one million Reichsmark (RM) each.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Total expenditure came to 2,618,259 RM, of which about 1,257,000 RM was spent on building and enlarging the sports venues and 1,099,000 RM on organisation and administration; the remainder covered items such as propaganda, temporary barracks and clean-up.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Income totalled 2,415,369 RM, including 1,253,831 RM in grants from the Garmisch and Partenkirchen municipalities, the city of Munich, the Bavarian state and the German government, and 1,010,618 RM from ticket sales.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Spending thus exceeded income by 202,890 RM, a shortfall the German government undertook to cover.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Much larger sums were spent outside the committee's accounts by the state railway, post office and broadcasting service, and on a new trunk road and the partial double-tracking of the Munich–Garmisch railway.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] The Games attracted the largest crowds of any Winter Olympics up to that point; one study judges that more people attended than at all the previous Winter Games combined.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] On ordinary competition days between 35,000 and 50,000 spectators were present in Garmisch-Partenkirchen, rising to about 64,000 on the first Sunday and an estimated 150,000 on the closing day, 16 February.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Between 5 and 17 February the state railway carried roughly 250,000 people to and from the town and the post office a further 13,000 by bus, while about 10,000 motor vehicles were in the town on the final day.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Special trains left Munich at intervals as short as ten minutes through the night, and directing the traffic on the narrow Alpine roads required several hundred police and auxiliaries.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] The Games also brought communications innovations.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] The opening ceremony took place on 6 February 1936 before a crowd of more than 30,000.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Cross-country skier Willy Bogner took the Olympic Oath on behalf of the competitors.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Alpine skiing appeared at the Olympics for the first time, contested as a combined event scoring each competitor's downhill and slalom runs; the German skiers Franz Pfnür and Christl Cranz won the men's and women's titles.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] A dispute between the International Ski Federation and the IOC over whether ski instructors could be regarded as amateurs led the Swiss and Austrian teams to boycott the alpine events.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] On the speed-skating oval, Norway's Ivar Ballangrud won three of the four races.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Sonja Henie of Norway secured her third consecutive Olympic title in figure skating.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Switzerland won the four-man bobsled in a combined time of 5:19.85, and Norway topped the overall medal table with seven gold, five silver and three bronze medals.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] The ice hockey tournament produced the Games' most contentious episode.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Most of the British team had learned the game in Canada, and Canada, the reigning Olympic champion, protested the inclusion of two of them—goaltender Jimmy Foster and forward Alex Archer—on the grounds that, having joined English clubs, they should be treated as professionals.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] The protest was withdrawn partway through the tournament as a gesture of goodwill, a concession Canada came to regret: with Foster in goal, Great Britain beat Canada 2–1—Edgar Brenchley scored the winning goal—and took the gold medal, ending Canada's run of four consecutive Olympic titles.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Because the Olympic tournament also counted as that year's World Championship, the British side became the first European team to be crowned world champions.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] The medals presented at the Games were the largest and heaviest awarded at any Olympics up to that date, measuring 100 mm in diameter and 4 mm thick.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] A total of 28 National Olympic Committees sent athletes to the Games.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Australia, Bulgaria, Greece, Liechtenstein, Spain and Turkey made their Winter Olympic debuts, while Estonia, Latvia, Luxembourg, the Netherlands and Yugoslavia returned after missing the 1932 Winter Olympics.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] The ten nations that won medals at the 1936 Winter Games are listed below; the host nation (Germany) is highlighted.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] Norway and Sweden each completed a podium sweep at the Games: Norway in the Nordic combined (Oddbjørn Hagen, Olaf Hoffsbakken and Sverre Brodahl), and Sweden in the men's 50 km cross-country (Elis Wiklund, Axel Wikström and Nils-Joel Englund).
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] The 1936 Winter Games let German organisers rehearse arrangements for security, transport, communications and crowd control that were used again at the Summer Olympics in Berlin.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] On the strength of the event, the IOC awarded the 1940 Winter Olympics to Garmisch-Partenkirchen, although those Games were cancelled after the outbreak of the Second World War.
[src:germany/1936-winter-olympics] On 7 March 1936, less than three weeks after the closing ceremony, Hitler ordered the remilitarization of the Rhineland, his first open breach of the Treaty of Versailles.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The **1954 FIFA World Cup** was the fifth edition of the FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial international football tournament for senior men's national teams of the nations affiliated to FIFA.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] It was held in Switzerland from 16 June to 4 July.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Switzerland was selected as the host country in July 1946.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] At the tournament, several all-time records for goalscoring were set, including the highest average number of goals scored per game.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The tournament was won by West Germany, who defeated tournament favourites Hungary 3–2 in the final for their first World Cup title.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Uruguay, the defending champions, were eliminated by Hungary in the semifinals and would lose to Austria in the match for third place.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The highest scoring match of a men’s World Cup happened in the quarterfinals of this tournament, when Austria defeated hosts Switzerland 7–5.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The 12 goals of that match have never been surpassed in a World Cup since.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] As of 2026, this is the last World Cup to not have a goalless draw.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Switzerland was awarded the tournament unopposed at a meeting in Luxembourg City on 22 July 1946, the same day Brazil was selected to host the 1950 World Cup.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The hosts (Switzerland) and the defending champions (Uruguay) qualified automatically.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Of the remaining 14 places, 11 were allocated to Europe (including Egypt, Turkey, and Israel), two to the Americas, and one to Asia.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Scotland, Turkey, and South Korea made their World Cup debuts at this tournament (Turkey and Scotland had qualified for the 1950 competition but both withdrew).
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] South Korea became the first independent Asian country to participate in a World Cup tournament.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Austria appeared following a hiatus from 1934.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Several teams, such as Hungary and Czechoslovakia were back into the tournament after missing out the 1950 World Cup.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] German teams as well as Japan were allowed to qualify again, after having been banned from the 1950 FIFA World Cup.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] West Germany qualified against fellow Germans from the Saarland (which then was a French protectorate), while East Germany did not enter, having cancelled international football matches after the East German uprising of 1953.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Argentina declined to participate for the third successive World Cup.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The following 16 teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The 1954 tournament used a unique format.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The sixteen qualified teams were divided into four groups of four teams each.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Each group contained two seeded teams and two unseeded teams.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Only four matches were scheduled for each group, each pitting a seeded team against an unseeded team.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] This contrasts with the usual round-robin in which every team plays every other team: six matches in each group.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Another oddity was that extra time, which in most tournaments is not employed at the group stage, was played in the group games if the score was level after 90 minutes, with the result being a draw if the scores were still level after 120 minutes.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Two points were awarded for a win and one for a draw.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The two teams with the most points from each group progressed to the knockout stage.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] In the case of a tie between two teams for second place, the two tied teams competed in a play-off to decide which team would progress to the next stage, with extra time and drawing of lots if necessary.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Two of the four groups ended up requiring play-offs – one between Switzerland and Italy, and the other between Turkey and West Germany.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] In each match, the unseeded team (Switzerland and West Germany) repeated an earlier victory against the seeded team (Italy and Turkey) to progress.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The fact that two group matches were played twice, while other group opponents never faced each other at all, attracted criticism; newly elected FIFA President Rodolphe Seeldrayers declared that this group format would be abandoned in future world cups.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] For each of the first two quarterfinals, one team progressing from group 1 was drawn against one team progressing from group 2.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] For the remaining two quarterfinals, this procedure was repeated for groups 3 and 4.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Before the tournament, it was stated that in the event of a quarterfinal being tied after 90 minutes, 30 minutes of extra time would be played, followed by drawing of lots if necessary.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Later, it was stated that a quarterfinal could be replayed in this situation.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The draw was scheduled to be held on Sunday 20 June, though in fact it was delayed into the early morning of Monday 21 June.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] For the semifinals, a further draw was held, with each semifinal featuring one team from groups 1–2 against one team from groups 3–4.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] In the event of a semifinal being tied after extra time, it would be replayed once, followed by drawing of lots if necessary.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The draw for the semifinals, held on Sunday 27 June, was delayed by a complaint from the Hungarian team concerning the manner in which their quarterfinal against Brazil had been played.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The final would be replayed if scores were level after extra-time.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] If the replay was also tied, the winner would be decided by the tournament organising committee, or by drawing of lots.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Before qualification was complete, the eight seeded teams were determined by FIFA.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] They were Austria, Brazil, England, France, Hungary, Italy, Spain, and Uruguay.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] These seedings were thrown into disarray when, in an unexpected result, Turkey eliminated Spain in qualification.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] FIFA resolved this situation by giving Turkey the seeding that had previously been allocated to Spain.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The Germany national football team, then limited to the area of West Germany only, had been reinstated as full FIFA members only in late 1950, had played only 18 games since, and were unseeded.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] When meeting the seeded Turkish side at Wankdorf stadium in Berne, the Turks scored early, but the Germans convincingly won the encounter, which would turn out as the first of two within six days.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The South Koreans, the other unseeded team, lost 7–0 and 9–0 against the seeded sides of Hungary and Turkey.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] West Germany, being denied the chance to play such an easy opponent, had to face the seeded team of Hungary, a favourite to win the World Cup.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Sepp Herberger, the West German coach, did not want his A-squad to suffer a possible defeat against a strong opponent while trying to qualify for a rather meaningless first place, and gambled by going the easier route into the play-offs and sending in a reserve side which lost 8–3 in Basel.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] A benefit was that the Hungarians did not get to know the best German players in case both teams would meet again - which they did, in the final, along with referee William Ling.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Now two teams were tied for second place on 2 points, and with no tie breaking procedures in effect, even though West Germany had beaten Turkey head-to-head, they had to play-off against each other, a match-up that West Germany easily won for the second time within six days, this time in Zürich.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Hungary's team captain Ferenc Puskás, considered by many as the best player in the world in that time, was injured by West German defender Werner Liebrich, and had to miss Hungary's next two matches.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Puskás played for Hungary in the final, despite still being in a questionable condition.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] In the quarterfinals, the favourites Hungary beat Brazil 4–2 in one of the most violent matches in football history, which became infamous as the Battle of Berne.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Meanwhile, the World Cup holders Uruguay sent England out of the tournament, also by 4–2.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] West Germany dispatched Yugoslavia 2–0, and Austria beat the host nation Switzerland in the game with the most goals in any World Cup match, 7–5.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] In the first semifinal, West Germany beat Austria 6–1.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] In the other semifinal, one of the most exciting games of the tournament, Hungary led Uruguay 1–0 at halftime, but the game went to extra time with a 2–2 score after 90 minutes.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The deadlock was broken by Sándor Kocsis with two late goals to take Hungary through to the final, with Uruguay finally losing their unbeaten record in World Cup Final matches.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Uruguay then went on to be beaten for a second time as Austria secured third place.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] At the Wankdorf Stadion in Berne, 60,000 people watched the final between West Germany and Hungary, a rematch of a first-round game, which Hungary had won 8–3 against the reserves of the German team.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The Golden Team of the Hungarians were favourites, as they were unbeaten for a record of 32 consecutive matches, but they had had two tough knockout matches.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] It started raining on match day–in Germany this was dubbed *Fritz-Walter-Wetter* ("Fritz Walter's weather") because the West German team captain Fritz Walter was said to play his best in the rain, a result of having contracted malaria during the war.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Adi Dassler of *Adidas* provided the West German team with a new kind of shoes, with exchangeable studs that were replaced during halftime.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Hungary's Ferenc Puskás played again in the final, even though he was not fully fit.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Despite this he put his team ahead after only six minutes and with Zoltán Czibor adding another two minutes later it seemed that the pre-tournament favourites would take the title.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] However, with a quick goal from Max Morlock in the 10th minute and an equaliser by Helmut Rahn in the 19th, the tide began to turn.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The second half featured telling misses by the Hungarian team.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Barely six minutes before the end of the match, the popular German radio reporter Herbert Zimmermann delivered the most famous line in the German commentary, recommending that "Rahn should shoot from deep", which he did.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The second goal from Rahn gave West Germany a 3–2 lead while the Hungarian reporter György Szepesi burst into tears.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Later, Zimmermann called Puskás offside before he kicked the ball into Toni Turek's net with 2 minutes left.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] While referee William Ling pointed to the centre spot, linesman Griffiths signalled offside.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] After a one-minute consultation, Ling disallowed the claimed equaliser.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] In Germany the success is known as the "Miracle of Bern" (*Das Wunder Von Bern*), and was memorialised in a 2003 film of the same name.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] For the Hungarians, the defeat was a disaster, and remains controversial for apparent refereeing errors and claims of doping.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] One controversy concerns the 2–2 equaliser.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Hungarian goalie Gyula Grosics jumped to catch Fritz Walter's corner shot, but Hans Schäfer obstructed him (in plain sight of TV cameras), allowing the ball to reach Rahn, who then scored.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Another controversy concerns allegations of doping.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Though teammates steadfastly denied this rumour, German historian Guido Knopp claimed in a 2004 documentary for German public channel ZDF that the players were injected with shots of vitamin C at half-time, using a needle earlier taken from a Soviet sports doctor.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] This resulted in both the better condition of the West German team in the second half and the wave of jaundice among their players following the tournament.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] A Leipzig University study in 2010 posited that the West German players had been injected with the banned substance methamphetamine.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Most controversial was the offside ruling for Puskás's intended 87th-minute equaliser.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The camera filming the official footage was in a bad position to judge the situation, but eyewitnesses claimed that the referee was wrong, including West German substitute player Alfred Pfaff.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] In 2004, North German regional public channel NDR aired unofficial footage appearing to show that Puskás was onside.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] For the first time there was television coverage, and special coins were issued to mark the event.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The 11 goals scored by Kocsis of Hungary not only led the World Cup but bettered the previous record (set by Brazilian Ademir in the previous tournament) by three goals.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Kocsis' mark was broken by Just Fontaine's 13 goals in 1958.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Despite not winning the 1954 tournament, their fourth-place finish and their two previous World Cup titles made Uruguay the most successful World Cup nation for eight years, until Brazil won their second title in 1962.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Hungary's 9–0 win against Korea during the group stages remains the biggest margin of victory in FIFA World Cup history, later equalled by Yugoslavia over Zaire (9–0) in 1974 and Hungary over El Salvador (10–1) in 1982.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] West Germany also became the first team to win the World Cup after having lost a match at the finals, losing 8–3 after pitting the backups against Hungary in the group stage with the intention of getting an additional play-off game.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] West Germany's 1954 victory remains the only time that a team has won the World Cup without playing any team from outside its own continent; South Korea was in the same group, but with both team unseeded, they were not matched against each other.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Instead, West Germany had to play Turkey twice, which is geographically more in Asia than in Europe, but qualified from Europe's qualification zone and has always been affiliated with UEFA.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Turkey had also been one of the few non-German speaking countries that had played West Germany after being reinstated as FIFA member in late 1950; and like most, did it twice, Switzerland even four times.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Thus, West Germany's coach and players had limited international experience in 1954, and no intercontinental game before the 1958 FIFA World Cup.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] West Germany's victory in the final is considered one of the greatest upsets of all time and one of the finest achievements in German sporting history.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] This is the only time a team has won the World Cup with amateur footballers.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Six venues in six cities (1 venue in each city) hosted the tournament's 26 matches.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Jakob Stadium in Basel, which hosted 6 matches.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The venues in Bern, Zurich and Lausanne each hosted 5 matches, the venue in Geneva hosted 4 matches, and the venue in Lugano only hosted 1 match.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] The 16 finalists named squads of 22 for the finals, though South Korea only named 20 players in their squad.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Unlike recent tournaments, there were no requirements for teams to name three goalkeepers; most teams did, but 6 did not.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Some teams also chose to leave some of their named squad at home, only bringing them to Switzerland if necessary.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] All times listed are local time (CET, UTC+1).
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] With 11 goals, Sándor Kocsis was the top scorer in the tournament.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] In total, 140 goals were scored by 63 players, with four of them credited as own goals.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] In 1986, FIFA published a report that ranked all teams in each World Cup up to and including 1986, based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:germany/1954-fifa-world-cup] Sönke Wortmann's 2003 German box-office hit *The Miracle of Bern* (in German: *Das Wunder von Bern*) re-tells the story of the German team's route to victory through the eyes of a young boy who admires the key player of the final, Helmut Rahn.
[src:germany/1955-saar-statute-referendum] A referendum on the Saar statute was held in the Saar Protectorate on 23 October 1955.
[src:germany/1955-saar-statute-referendum] The statute would have made the territory an independent polity under the auspices of a European Commissioner, to be appointed by the Council of Ministers of the Western European Union, while remaining in the economic union with France.
[src:germany/1955-saar-statute-referendum] Its rejection by voters was taken as an indication that they would rather reunite with West Germany.
[src:germany/1955-saar-statute-referendum] On 27 October 1956 France and West Germany concluded the Saar Treaty establishing that Saarland should be allowed to join West Germany as provided by article 23 of its constitution (Grundgesetz).
[src:germany/1955-saar-statute-referendum] Saarland subsequently became a state of Germany with effect from 1 January 1957.
[src:germany/de] The name is based on the first two letters of the German name for Germany (*Deutschland*).
[src:germany/de] Prior to 1990, East Germany had a separate ISO 3166-1 code (*dd*), and had never delegated a ccTLD, .dd.
[src:germany/de] .de is currently the second most popular ccTLD in terms of number of registrations with .cn being the first most popular ccTLD and .uk being third.
[src:germany/de] It is third after .com and .cn among all TLDs.
[src:germany/de] The first point of registration for .de domains was at the Department of Computer Science of the University of Dortmund.
[src:germany/de] *uni-dortmund.de* was among the first registered .de-domains.
[src:germany/de] .de registrations may be directly ordered from DENIC but it is faster and cheaper to do so via a DENIC member (registrar).
[src:germany/de] Previously, domain names had to be at least three letters long.
[src:germany/de] There were a few two-letter domains registered before the rule was put in place: db.de (Deutsche Bahn, German Railways), ix.de (the German computing magazine iX), and hq.de.
[src:germany/de] Another domain, bb.de (Bilfinger Berger), was later deregistered (and after 2009 registered by another company).
[src:germany/de] As a result of a lawsuit by Volkswagen, which wanted to register the two-letter domain "vw.de", after 23 October 2009, DENIC was forced to allow the registration of single- and two-letter domains as well as number-only domains, such as 123.de, xx.de or v.de.
[src:germany/de] Registrations of internationalized domain names (IDN) are also accepted so that all diacritics of German, many diacritics of other languages and the eszett, ß, may be used.
[src:germany/de] In many of the Romance languages, e.g., Spanish, French, Romanian and Portuguese, "*de*" expresses the genitive of a noun (like "*of*" in English).
[src:germany/de] This is exploited in domain registrations under the German TLD for romance language webhosts that offer customized sites, like *elforo.de* (theforum.of), encoding the site name into the URL path, such as *elforo.de/wikipedia*, meaning theforum.of/Wikipedia.
[src:germany/de] In accordance with IANA policy, `.dd` would have been available to be assigned in the root nameservers as the country code top-level domain (ccTLD) for East Germany.
[src:germany/de] Its only use was internally in an isolated network among the universities of Jena and Dresden.
[src:germany/de] With the reunification of Germany, East Germany became part of the Federal Republic of Germany (West Germany), which had already been assigned the ccTLD `.de`.
[src:germany/de] The ISO 3166-1 code "DD" was withdrawn in 1990.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Settlement in the territory of modern Germany began in the Lower Paleolithic, with various tribes inhabiting it from the Neolithic onward, chiefly the Celts, and Germanic tribes inhabiting the north.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 962, the Kingdom of Germany formed the bulk of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:germany/germany-p01] During the 16th century, northern German regions became the centre of the Protestant Reformation.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Following the Napoleonic Wars and the dissolution of the Holy Roman Empire in 1806, the German Confederation was formed in 1815.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Unification of Germany into the modern nation-state, led by Prussia, established the German Empire in 1871.
[src:germany/germany-p01] After World War I and a revolution, the Empire was replaced by the Weimar Republic.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The Nazi rise to power in 1933 led to the establishment of a totalitarian dictatorship, World War II, and the Holocaust.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 1949, after the war and Allied occupation, Germany was organised into two separate polities with limited sovereignty: the Federal Republic of Germany (FRG), or West Germany, and the German Democratic Republic (GDR), or East Germany.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The FRG was a founding member of the European Economic Community, while the GDR was a communist Eastern Bloc state and a founding member of the Warsaw Pact.
[src:germany/germany-p01] After the fall of the communist-led government in East Germany, German reunification saw the former East German states join the FRG on 3 October 1990.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany is a developed country with a strong economy; it has the largest economy in Europe by nominal GDP.
[src:germany/germany-p01] As a major force in several industrial, scientific and technological sectors, Germany is both the world's third-largest exporter and third-largest importer.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Widely considered a great power, Germany is part of multiple international organisations and forums.
[src:germany/germany-p01] It has the third-highest number of UNESCO World Heritage Sites: 55, of which 52 are cultural.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The English word *Germany* derives from the Latin *Germania*, which came into use after Julius Caesar adopted it for the peoples east of the Rhine.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The German term *Deutschland*, originally *diutisciu land* ('the German lands'), is derived from *deutsch* (cf.
[src:germany/germany-p01] *Dutch*), which descended from Old High German *diutisc* 'of the people' (from *diot* or *diota* 'people'), originally used to distinguish the language of the common people from Latin and its Romance descendants.
[src:germany/germany-p01] This in turn descends from Proto-Germanic **þiudiskaz* 'of the people' (see also the Latinised form *Theodiscus*), derived from **þeudō*, descended from Proto-Indo-European **tewtéh₂-* 'people', from which the word *Teutons* also originates.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Ancient humans were present in Germany at least 600,000 years ago.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The first non-modern human fossil (the Neanderthal) was discovered in the Neander Valley.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Similarly dated evidence of modern humans has been found in the Swabian Jura, including 42,000-year-old flutes which are the oldest musical instruments ever found, the 40,000-year-old Lion Man, and the 41,000-year-old Venus of Hohle Fels.
[src:germany/germany-p01] From southern Scandinavia and northern Germany, the Germanic peoples expanded south, east, and west, coming into contact with the Celtic, Iranian, Baltic, and Slavic tribes.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Southern Germany was inhabited by Celtic-speaking peoples, who belonged to the wider La Tène culture.
[src:germany/germany-p01] They were later assimilated by the Germanic conquerors.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Under Augustus, the Roman Empire began to invade lands inhabited by the Germanic tribes, creating a short-lived Roman province of Germania between the Rhine and Elbe rivers.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 9 AD, three Roman legions were defeated by Arminius in the Battle of the Teutoburg Forest.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The outcome of this battle dissuaded the Romans from their ambition of conquering Germania and is thus considered one of the most significant events in European history.
[src:germany/germany-p01] By 100 AD, when Tacitus wrote *Germania*, Germanic tribes had settled along the Rhine and the Danube (the Limes Germanicus), occupying most of modern Germany.
[src:germany/germany-p01] However, Baden-Württemberg, southern Bavaria, southern Hesse and the western Rhineland had been incorporated into Roman provinces.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Around 260, Germanic peoples broke into Roman-controlled lands.
[src:germany/germany-p01] After the invasion of the Huns in 375, and with the decline of Rome from 395, Germanic tribes moved farther southwest: the Franks established the Frankish Kingdom and pushed east to subjugate Saxony and Bavaria.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Areas of modern eastern Germany were inhabited by Western Slavic tribes.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Charlemagne founded the Carolingian Empire in 800; it was divided in 843.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The eastern successor kingdom of East Francia stretched from the Rhine in the west to the Elbe river in the east and from the North Sea to the Alps.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Subsequently, the Kingdom of Germany and the Holy Roman Empire emerged from it.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The Ottonian rulers (919–1024) consolidated several major duchies.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 996, Gregory V became the first German Pope, appointed by his cousin Otto III, whom he shortly after crowned Holy Roman Emperor.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The Holy Roman Empire absorbed northern Italy and Burgundy under the Salian emperors (1024–1125), although the emperors lost power through the Investiture Controversy.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Under the Hohenstaufen emperors (1138–1254), German princes encouraged German settlement to the south and east (*Ostsiedlung*).
[src:germany/germany-p01] Members of the Hanseatic League, mostly north German towns, prospered in the expansion of trade.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The population declined starting with the Great Famine in 1315, followed by the Black Death of 1348–1350.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The Golden Bull issued in 1356 provided the constitutional structure of the Empire and codified the election of the emperor by seven prince-electors.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Johannes Gutenberg introduced moveable-type printing to Europe, laying the basis for the democratisation of knowledge.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Following Martin Luther's 1517 Protestant Reformation, bolstered by his standardised Bible translation, led to the 1555 Peace of Augsburg, which recognised Lutheranism under the principle of *cuius regio, eius religio* (ruler's faith dictates subjects' faith).
[src:germany/germany-p01] From the Cologne War through the Thirty Years' Wars (1618–1648), religious conflict devastated German lands and significantly reduced the population.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The Peace of Westphalia ended religious warfare among the Imperial Estates.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The legal system initiated by a series of Imperial Reforms (approximately 1495–1555) provided for considerable local autonomy and a stronger Imperial Diet.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The House of Habsburg held the imperial crown from 1438 until the death of Charles VI in 1740.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Following the War of the Austrian Succession and the Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle, Charles VI's daughter Maria Theresa ruled as empress consort when her husband, Francis I, became emperor.
[src:germany/germany-p01] From 1740, dualism between the Austrian Habsburg monarchy and the Kingdom of Prussia dominated German history.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 1772, 1793, and 1795, Prussia and Austria, along with the Russian Empire, agreed to the Partitions of Poland.
[src:germany/germany-p01] During the period of the French Revolutionary Wars, the Napoleonic era and the subsequent final meeting of the Imperial Diet, most of the Free Imperial Cities were annexed by dynastic territories; the ecclesiastical territories were secularised and annexed.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 1806 the *Imperium* was dissolved; France, Russia, Prussia, and the Habsburgs (Austria) competed for hegemony in the German states during the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Following the fall of Napoleon, the Congress of Vienna founded the German Confederation, a loose league of 39 sovereign states.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The appointment of the emperor of Austria as the permanent president reflected the Congress' rejection of Prussia's rising influence.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Disagreement within restoration politics partly led to the rise of liberal movements, followed by new measures of repression by Austrian statesman Klemens von Metternich.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The *Zollverein*, a tariff union, furthered economic unity.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In light of revolutionary movements in Europe, intellectuals and commoners started the revolutions of 1848 in the German states, raising the German question.
[src:germany/germany-p01] King Frederick William IV of Prussia was offered the title of emperor, but with a loss of power; he rejected the crown and the proposed constitution, a temporary setback for the movement.
[src:germany/germany-p01] King William I appointed Otto von Bismarck as the Minister President of Prussia in 1862.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Bismarck successfully concluded the war with Denmark in 1864; the subsequent decisive Prussian victory in the Austro-Prussian War of 1866 enabled him to create the North German Confederation which excluded Austria.
[src:germany/germany-p01] After the defeat of France in the Franco-Prussian War, the German princes proclaimed the founding of the German Empire in 1871.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Prussia was the dominant constituent state of the new empire; the King of Prussia ruled as its Emperor (*Kaiser*), and Berlin became its capital.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In the *Gründerzeit* period following the unification of Germany, Bismarck's foreign policy as chancellor of Germany secured Germany's position as a great nation by forging alliances and avoiding war.
[src:germany/germany-p01] However, under Wilhelm II, Germany took an imperialistic course, leading to friction with neighbouring countries.
[src:germany/germany-p01] A dual alliance was created with the multinational realm of Austria-Hungary; the Triple Alliance of 1882 included Italy.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Britain, France and Russia also concluded alliances to protect against Habsburg interference with Russian interests in the Balkans or German interference against France.
[src:germany/germany-p01] At the Berlin Conference in 1884, Germany claimed several colonies including German East Africa, German South West Africa, Togoland, and Kamerun.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany later expanded its colonial empire to include holdings in the Pacific and China.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The colonial government in South West Africa (present-day Namibia), from 1904 to 1908, carried out the annihilation of the local Herero and Nama peoples as punishment for an uprising; this was the 20th century's first genocide.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The assassination of Austria's crown prince on 28 June 1914 provided the pretext for Austria-Hungary to attack Serbia and trigger World War I.
[src:germany/germany-p01] After four years of warfare, in which approximately two million German soldiers were killed, a general armistice ended the fighting.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In the German Revolution (November 1918), Wilhelm II and the ruling princes abdicated their positions.
[src:germany/germany-p01] On 9 November 1918, Philipp Scheidemann, a Social Democrat, proclaimed the German Republic, marking Germany's transition to a federal democratic state.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany's new leadership signed the Treaty of Versailles in 1919, accepting defeat by the Allies.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germans perceived the treaty as humiliating, which was seen by historians as influential in the rise of Adolf Hitler.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany lost around 13% of its European territory and ceded all of its colonial possessions.
[src:germany/germany-p01] On 11 August 1919, President Friedrich Ebert signed the democratic Weimar Constitution.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Communists briefly seized power in Bavaria and a few larger cities, while conservative elements failed to overthrow the central government in the 1920 Kapp Putsch.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The occupation of the Ruhr by Belgian and French troops and a period of hyperinflation followed.
[src:germany/germany-p01] A plan to restructure Germany's war reparations and the creation of a new currency in 1924 helped stabilise the government and ushered in the Golden Twenties, an era of artistic innovation and liberal cultural life.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 1929, the Great Depression hit Germany, and by 1932 the unemployment rate had risen to nearly 30%.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The Nazi Party led by Adolf Hitler became the largest party in the Reichstag after the election of July 1932, and President Hindenburg appointed Hitler chancellor on 30 January 1933.
[src:germany/germany-p01] After the Reichstag fire, a decree abrogated basic civil rights, and the first Nazi concentration camp opened.
[src:germany/germany-p01] On 23 March 1933, the Enabling Act gave Hitler unrestricted legislative power, overriding the constitution, and marked the beginning of Nazi Germany.
[src:germany/germany-p01] His government established a centralised totalitarian state, withdrew from the League of Nations, and dramatically increased Germany's rearmament.
[src:germany/germany-p01] A government-sponsored programme for economic renewal focused on public works, the most famous of which was the *Autobahn*.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 1935, the regime withdrew from the Treaty of Versailles and introduced the Nuremberg Laws which targeted Jews and other minorities.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany also reacquired control of the Saarland in 1935, remilitarised the Rhineland in 1936, annexed Austria in 1938, annexed the Sudetenland in 1938 with the Munich Agreement, and, in violation of the agreement, occupied Czechoslovakia in March 1939.
[src:germany/germany-p01] *Kristallnacht* (Night of Broken Glass) saw the burning of synagogues, the destruction of Jewish businesses, and mass arrests of Jewish people.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In August 1939, Hitler's government negotiated the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact that divided Eastern Europe into German and Soviet spheres of influence.
[src:germany/germany-p01] On 1 September 1939, Germany invaded Poland, beginning World War II in Europe; Britain and France declared war on Germany on 3 September.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In spring 1940, Germany conquered Denmark and Norway, the Netherlands, Belgium, Luxembourg, and France.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The British repelled German air attacks in the Battle of Britain in the same year.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 1941, German troops invaded Yugoslavia, Greece and the Soviet Union, and Germany declared war on the United States.
[src:germany/germany-p01] By 1942, Germany and its allies controlled most of continental Europe and North Africa, but following the Soviet victory at the Battle of Stalingrad, the Allied reconquest of North Africa and invasion of Italy in 1943, German forces suffered repeated military defeats.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 1944, the Soviets pushed into Eastern Europe; the Western allies landed in France and entered Germany despite a final German counteroffensive.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Following Hitler's suicide during the Battle of Berlin, Germany signed the surrender document on 8 May 1945, ending World War II in Europe and Nazi Germany.
[src:germany/germany-p01] After the war, surviving Nazi officials were tried for war crimes at the Nuremberg trials.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Discrimination was institutionalised through legislation and perpetrated at an industrial scale with concentration and death camps across Europe.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The crimes against humanity culminated but were not limited to what later became known as the Holocaust, the systematic murdering of around 6 million Jews.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Several other minority groups were targeted: at least 130,000 Romani, 275,000 disabled, thousands of Jehovah's Witnesses, thousands of homosexuals, and hundreds of thousands of political and religious opponents.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Nazi policies in German-occupied countries resulted in the deaths of an estimated 2.7 million Poles, 1.3 million Ukrainians, 1 million Belarusians and 3.5 million Soviet prisoners of war.
[src:germany/germany-p01] German military casualties have been estimated at 5.3 million, and around 900,000 German civilians died.
[src:germany/germany-p01] During the later stages of and after World War II, around 12 million ethnic Germans were expelled from across Eastern Europe, and Germany lost roughly one-quarter of its pre-war territory.
[src:germany/germany-p01] After the surrender of Nazi Germany, the Allies *de jure* abolished the German state and partitioned Berlin and Germany's remaining territory into four occupation zones.
[src:germany/germany-p01] They were informally known as West Germany and East Germany.
[src:germany/germany-p01] East Germany selected East Berlin as its capital, while West Germany chose Bonn as a provisional capital to emphasize its stance that the two-state solution was temporary.
[src:germany/germany-p01] West Germany was established as a federal parliamentary republic with a social market economy.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 1948, West Germany became a major recipient of reconstruction aid under the American Marshall Plan.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Konrad Adenauer was elected the first federal chancellor of Germany in 1949.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The country enjoyed prolonged economic growth (*Wirtschaftswunder*) beginning in the early 1950s.
[src:germany/germany-p01] West Germany joined NATO in 1955 and was a founding member of the European Economic Community.
[src:germany/germany-p01] On 1 January 1957, the Saarland joined West Germany.
[src:germany/germany-p01] East Germany remained under political and military control by the Soviet Union via occupation forces and became an Eastern Bloc state, joining the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact and Comecon.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Although East Germany claimed to be a democracy, political power was exercised solely by leading members (*Politbüro*) of the Socialist Unity Party of Germany that was closely aligned with the Communist Party of the Soviet Union.
[src:germany/germany-p01] An extensive domestic intelligence programme led by the intelligence agency Stasi was launched that utilized a vast network of informants to crush dissent.
[src:germany/germany-p01] While East German propaganda was based on the benefits of the GDR's social programmes and the alleged threat of a West German invasion, many of its citizens looked to the West for freedom and prosperity.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The Berlin Wall, built in 1961, prevented East German citizens from escaping to West Germany, becoming a symbol of the Cold War.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Tensions between East and West Germany were reduced in the late 1960s by Chancellor Willy Brandt's *Ostpolitik*.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 1989, Hungary dismantled the Iron Curtain and opened its Austrian border, triggering a mass emigration of East Germans to West Germany.
[src:germany/germany-p01] This had devastating effects on the GDR, where regular mass demonstrations received increasing support.
[src:germany/germany-p01] This permitted German reunification on 3 October 1990, with the dissolution of the GDR and the accession of the five re-established states to the FDR.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989 became a symbol of the fall of Communism, the dissolution of the Soviet Union, German reunification and *Die Wende* ("the turning point").
[src:germany/germany-p01] United Germany was considered the enlarged continuation of West Germany, so it retained its memberships in international organisations.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Based on the Berlin/Bonn Act of 1994, Berlin again became the capital of Germany, while Bonn obtained the unique status of a *Bundesstadt* (federal city), retaining some federal ministries.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The relocation of the government was completed in 1999, and modernisation of the East German economy was scheduled to last until 2019.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Since reunification, Germany has taken a more active role in the European Union, signing the Maastricht Treaty in 1992 and the Lisbon Treaty in 2007, and co-founding the eurozone.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany sent a peacekeeping force to secure stability in the Balkans and sent German troops to Afghanistan as part of a NATO effort to provide security in that country after the ousting of the Taliban.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In the 2005 elections, Angela Merkel became the first female chancellor.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2009, the German government approved a €50 billion stimulus plan.
[src:germany/germany-p01] During the 2015 European migrant crisis, the country took in over a million refugees and migrants.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany is the seventh-largest country in Europe.
[src:germany/germany-p01] It borders Denmark to the north; Poland and the Czech Republic to the east; Austria and Switzerland to the south; and France, Luxembourg, Belgium, and the Netherlands to the west.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany is also bordered by the North Sea and, at the north-northeast, the Baltic Sea.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Elevation ranges from the mountains of the Alps (with the highest point being the Zugspitze at 2,963 metres or 9,721 feet) in the south to the shores of the North Sea (*Nordsee*) in the northwest and the Baltic Sea (*Ostsee*) in the northeast.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The forested uplands of central Germany and the lowlands of northern Germany (lowest point: in the municipality Neuendorf-Sachsenbande, Wilstermarsch, at 3.54 metres or 11.6 feet below sea level) are traversed by such major rivers as the Rhine, Danube and Elbe.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Significant natural resources include iron ore, coal, potash, timber, lignite, uranium, copper, natural gas, salt, and nickel.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Most of Germany has a temperate climate, ranging from oceanic in the north and west to continental in the east and southeast.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Winters range from cold in the Southern Alps to cool and are generally overcast with limited precipitation, while summers can vary from hot and dry to cool and rainy.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The northern regions have prevailing westerly winds that bring in moist air from the North Sea, moderating the temperature and increasing precipitation.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Conversely, the southeast regions have more extreme temperatures.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Climate change in Germany is leading to long-term impacts on agriculture, more intense heat waves and cold waves, flash and coastal flooding, and reduced water availability.
[src:germany/germany-p01] From February 2019–February 2020, average monthly temperatures in Germany ranged from a low of 3.3 °C (37.9 °F) in January 2020 to a high of 19.8 °C (67.6 °F) in June 2019.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Average monthly precipitation ranged from 30 litres per square metre in February and April 2019 to 125 litres per square metre in February 2020.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Average monthly hours of sunshine ranged from 45 in November 2019 to 300 in June 2019.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The territory of Germany can be divided into five terrestrial ecoregions: Atlantic mixed forests, Baltic mixed forests, Central European mixed forests, Western European broadleaf forests, and Alps conifer and mixed forests.
[src:germany/germany-p01] As of 2016, 51% of Germany's land area is devoted to agriculture, while 30% is forested and 14% is covered by settlements or infrastructure.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Plants and animals include those generally common to Central Europe.
[src:germany/germany-p01] According to the National Forest Inventory, beeches, oaks, and other deciduous trees constitute just over 40% of the forests; roughly 60% are conifers, particularly spruce and pine.
[src:germany/germany-p01] There are many species of ferns, flowers, fungi, and mosses.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Wild animals include roe deer, wild boar, mouflon (a subspecies of wild sheep), fox, badger, hare, and small numbers of the Eurasian beaver.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The blue cornflower was once a German national symbol.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In addition, there are 17 Biosphere Reserves, and 105 nature parks.
[src:germany/germany-p01] More than 400 zoos and animal parks operate in Germany.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The Berlin Zoo, which opened in 1844, is the oldest in Germany, and claims the most comprehensive collection of species in the world.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany is a federal, parliamentary, representative democratic republic.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Federal legislative power is vested in the parliament consisting of the *Bundestag* (Federal Diet) and *Bundesrat* (Federal Council), which together form the legislative body.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The *Bundestag* is elected through direct elections using the mixed-member proportional representation system.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The members of the *Bundesrat* represent and are appointed by the governments of the sixteen federated states.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The German political system operates under a framework laid out in the 1949 constitution known as the *Grundgesetz* (Basic Law).
[src:germany/germany-p01] Amendments generally require a two-thirds majority of both the *Bundestag* and the *Bundesrat*; the fundamental principles of the constitution, as expressed in the articles guaranteeing human dignity, the separation of powers, the federal structure, and the rule of law, are valid in perpetuity.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The president, who has been Frank-Walter Steinmeier since 2017, is the head of state and invested primarily with representative responsibilities and powers.
[src:germany/germany-p01] He is elected by the *Bundesversammlung* (federal convention), an institution consisting of the members of the *Bundestag* and an equal number of state delegates.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The second-highest official in the German order of precedence is the *Bundestagspräsident* (president of the Bundestag), who is elected by the *Bundestag* and responsible for overseeing the daily sessions of the body.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The third-highest official and the head of government is the chancellor, who is appointed by the *Bundespräsident* after being elected by the party or coalition with the most seats in the *Bundestag*.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The chancellor, who has been Friedrich Merz since 2025, is the head of government and exercises executive power through his Cabinet.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Since 1949, the party system has been dominated by the centre-right Christian Democratic Union and the centre-left Social Democratic Party.
[src:germany/germany-p01] So far every chancellor has been a member of one of these parties.
[src:germany/germany-p01] However, the smaller liberal Free Democratic Party and Alliance 90/The Greens have also been junior partners in coalition governments.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Since 2007, the democratic socialist party The Left has been a staple in the German *Bundestag*, as has the far-right Alternative for Germany since 2017.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany is a federation comprising sixteen constituent states referred to as *Länder*, thirteen of which are so-called "area-states" (*Flächenländer*).
[src:germany/germany-p01] Two states, Berlin and Hamburg, are city-states (*Stadtstaaten*), in which there is no separation between state government and local administration.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The state of Bremen, though officially also called a *Stadtstaat*, consists of the cities of Bremen, for which the state government also serves as the municipal administration, and the exclave of Bremerhaven.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Each state (*Land*) has its own constitution and is largely autonomous in its organisation.
[src:germany/germany-p01] As of 2017, Germany is divided into 401 districts (*Kreise*) at a municipal level; these consist of 294 rural districts and 107 urban districts.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany has a civil law system based on Roman law with some references to Germanic law.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The *Bundesverfassungsgericht* (Federal Constitutional Court) is the German Supreme Court responsible for constitutional matters, with power of judicial review.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany's specialised supreme court system includes the Federal Court of Justice for civil and criminal cases, along with the Federal Labour Court, Federal Social Court, Federal Fiscal Court, and Federal Administrative Court for other matters.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Criminal and private laws are codified on the national level in the *Strafgesetzbuch* and the *Bürgerliches Gesetzbuch* respectively.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The German penal system seeks the rehabilitation of the criminal and the protection of the public.
[src:germany/germany-p01] With the exceptions of petty crimes, tried by a single professional judge, and of serious political crimes, all charges are adjudicated by mixed tribunals where lay judges (*Schöffen*) and professional judges preside together.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2016, Germany's murder rate stood at a low of 1.18 murders per 100,000.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2018, the overall crime rate in the country fell to its lowest since 1992, while in 2024, it was reported that violent crime reached a 15-year high, with overall crime rising as well.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Same-sex marriage in Germany has been legal since 2017, and LGBT rights in the country are generally protected.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany has a network of 227 diplomatic missions abroad and maintains relations with more than 190 countries.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany is a member of the Council of Europe, NATO, the OECD, the G7, the G20, the World Bank and the IMF.
[src:germany/germany-p01] It has played an influential role in the European Union since its inception and has maintained a strong alliance with France and all neighbouring countries since 1990.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany promotes the creation of a more unified European political, economic and security apparatus.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Because of its economic power and political influence, Germany is widely considered to be a great power.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The governments of Germany and the United States are close political allies.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Cultural ties and economic interests have crafted a bond between the two countries resulting in Atlanticism.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany's development policy functions as a distinct sector within its foreign policy framework.
[src:germany/germany-p01] It is formulated by the Federal Ministry for Economic Cooperation and Development and carried out by the implementing organisations.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The German government sees development policy as a joint responsibility of the international community.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany was the world's second-biggest aid donor in 2019 after the United States.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany's military, the *Bundeswehr* (Federal Defence), is organised into the *Heer* (Army and special forces KSK), *Marine* (Navy), *Luftwaffe* (Air Force) and *Cyber- und Informationsraum* (Cyber and Information Domain Service) branches.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In absolute terms, German military spending in 2025 was the fourth-highest in the world.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In response to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, Chancellor Olaf Scholz announced that German military expenditure would be increased past the NATO target of 2%, along with a one-time 2022 infusion of 100 billion euros, representing almost double the 53 billion euro military budget for 2021.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2023, military spending according to NATO criteria amounted to $73.1 billion, or 1.64% of the country's GDP, well below the NATO target of 2%.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2024, Germany reported $97.7 billion to NATO, exceeding said target at 2.12% of GDP.
[src:germany/germany-p01] As of May 2024, the *Bundeswehr* has a strength of 180,215 active soldiers and 80,761 civilians.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Reservists are available to the armed forces and participate in defence exercises and deployments abroad.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Until 2011, military service was compulsory for men at age 18, but this has been officially suspended and replaced with a voluntary service.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Since 2001 women may serve in all functions of service without restriction.
[src:germany/germany-p01] According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute, Germany was the fourth-largest exporter of major arms in the world between 2021 and 2025.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In peacetime, the *Bundeswehr* is commanded by the Minister of Defence.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In a state of defence, the Chancellor would become commander-in-chief of the *Bundeswehr*.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The role of the *Bundeswehr* is described in the Constitution of Germany as defensive only.
[src:germany/germany-p01] But after a ruling of the Federal Constitutional Court in 1994, the term "defence" has been defined not only to include protection of the borders of Germany, but also crisis reaction and conflict prevention, or more broadly as guarding the security of Germany anywhere in the world.
[src:germany/germany-p01] As of 2026, the German military has about 3,000 troops stationed in foreign countries including 1,800 in Lithuania and nearby countries, about 300 in Kosovo, 300 in Iraq and Jordan, and 200 in Lebanon.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany has a social market economy with a highly skilled labour force, a low level of corruption, and a high level of innovation.
[src:germany/germany-p01] It is the largest economy in Europe by nominal GDP, as well as the world's third-largest by nominal GDP and sixth-largest by PPP-adjusted GDP.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Its PPP-adjusted GDP per capita amounted to 115% of the EU average in 2024.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The country's service sector contributes approximately 72% of the total GDP, the industrial sector 27%—with Germany having the largest manufacturing output in Europe—and its agricultural sector 1%, as of 2023.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The unemployment rate published by Eurostat amounts to 3.2% as of January 2020, which is the fourth-lowest in the EU.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany is part of the European single market which represents more than 450 million consumers.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2017, the country accounted for 28% of the eurozone economy according to the International Monetary Fund.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany introduced the common EU currency, the euro, in 2002.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Its monetary policy is set by the European Central Bank, which is based in Frankfurt, the country's largest financial centre.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany is the world's third-largest exporter and third-largest importer, and it has the second-largest trade surplus after China.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Its largest trading partners in 2025 were China, the United States and the Netherlands.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany's main exports are vehicles, machinery, and chemical goods.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The German automotive industry is among the most competitive and innovative in the world.
[src:germany/germany-p01] It was the sixth-largest by production and largest by export value in 2023.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany is home to Volkswagen Group, the world's second-largest automotive manufacturer by vehicle production.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Of the world's 500 largest stock market-listed companies by revenue in 2024, the *Fortune* Global 500, 29 were based in Germany.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The DAX, Germany's stock market index operated by the Frankfurt Stock Exchange, includes 30 major Germany-based companies.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Prominent German companies include Mercedes-Benz, BMW, Volkswagen, Audi, Porsche, Siemens, Adidas, SAP, Bosch and BASF.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Berlin is a hub for startup companies and has become the leading location for venture capital-funded firms in the EU.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany is recognised for its large portion of specialised small and medium enterprises known as the *Mittelstand*; these companies represent around 48% of the global market leaders in their segments, labelled hidden champions.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Research and development efforts form an integral part of the German economy, with the country ranking fourth in research and development expenditure since 2005.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2018, Germany ranked fourth globally in terms of number of science and engineering research papers published and third in the quality-adjusted Nature Index in 2023.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Well-known research institutions in Germany include the Max Planck Society, the Helmholtz Association, the Fraunhofer Society, and the Leibniz Association.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany is the largest contributor to the European Space Agency.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The country was ranked 11th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:germany/germany-p01] With its central position in Europe, Germany is a transport hub for the continent.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Its road network is among the densest in Europe.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The motorway (*Autobahn*) is widely known for having no general federally mandated speed limit for some classes of vehicles.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The Intercity Express or *ICE* train network serves major German cities as well as destinations in neighbouring countries with speeds up to 300 km/h (190 mph).
[src:germany/germany-p01] The largest German airports are Frankfurt Airport, Munich Airport and Berlin Brandenburg Airport.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The Port of Hamburg is the third-busiest port in Europe and one of the twenty largest container ports in the world.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2019, Germany was the world's seventh-largest consumer of energy.
[src:germany/germany-p01] All German nuclear power plants were phased out in 2023.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany meets its power demands using 40% renewable sources (2018), and has been called an "early leader" in solar panels and offshore wind.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The German energy transition (*Energiewende*) is the recognised move to a sustainable economy by means of energy efficiency and renewable energy, with the country being called "the world's first major renewable energy economy".
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany has reduced its primary energy consumption by 11% between 1990 and 2015 and set itself goals of reducing it by 30% until 2030 and 50% by 2050.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The country is committed to the Paris Agreement and several other treaties promoting biodiversity, low emission standards, and water management.
[src:germany/germany-p01] As of 2017, Germany's household recycling rate is among the highest in the world, at around 65%.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2023, Germany was the 14th highest emitting nation of greenhouse gases.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Domestic and international travel and tourism directly contributed over €105.3 billion to German GDP in 2015.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Including indirect and induced impacts, the industry supported nearly 4.2 million jobs in 2015.
[src:germany/germany-p01] As of 2024, Germany is the seventh-most-visited country.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Its most popular landmarks include Cologne Cathedral, the Brandenburg Gate, the Reichstag, the Dresden Frauenkirche, Neuschwanstein Castle, Heidelberg Castle, the Wartburg, and Sanssouci Palace.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Europa-Park near Freiburg is Europe's second-most popular theme park resort.
[src:germany/germany-p01] With a population of 84.7 million according to the 2023 German census, Germany is the most populous member state of the European Union, the second-most populous country in Europe after Russia, and the nineteenth-most populous country in the world.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Its population density stands at 236 inhabitants per square kilometre (610 inhabitants/mi2).
[src:germany/germany-p01] The fertility rate of 1.57 children born per woman (2022 estimates) is below the replacement rate of 2.1 and is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Since the 1970s, Germany's death rate has exceeded its birth rate.
[src:germany/germany-p01] However, the country is witnessing increased birth and migration rates since the early 2010s.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany has the fourth oldest population in the world, with an average age of 47.8 years.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany is a major destination for immigrants, ranking second in the world after the United States.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2015, following the 2015 refugee crisis, the Population Division of the United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs listed Germany as host to the second-highest number of international migrants worldwide, about 5% or 12 million of all 244 million migrants.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Refugee crises have resulted in substantial population increases; for example, the major influx of Ukrainian immigrants following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, whereby over 1.06 million refugees from Ukraine were recorded in Germany as of April 2023.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2019, Germany ranked seventh among EU countries in terms of the percentage of migrants in the country's population, at 13.1%.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2022, there were 23.8 million people—28.7 percent of the total population—who had a migration background.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany has over 2,000 cities and towns, and 11 officially recognised metropolitan regions.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The country's most populous city is Berlin, and its largest urban area is the Ruhr.
[src:germany/germany-p01] German is the official and predominantly spoken language in Germany.
[src:germany/germany-p01] It is one of 24 official and working languages of the European Union, and one of the three procedural languages of the European Commission, alongside English and French.
[src:germany/germany-p01] German is the most widely spoken first language in the European Union, with around 100 million native speakers.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Recognised native minority languages in Germany are Danish, Low German, Low Rhenish, Sorbian, Romani, North Frisian and Saterland Frisian; they are officially protected by the European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The most used immigrant languages are Turkish, Arabic, Kurdish, Polish, Italian, Greek, Spanish, Serbo-Croatian, Bulgarian and other Balkan languages, as well as Russian.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germans are typically multilingual: 74% of German citizens claim to be able to communicate in at least one foreign language and 35% in at least two.
[src:germany/germany-p01] According to the 2022 census, Christianity is the largest religion in Germany at 49.7% of the population; 23.1% identified as Protestant and 25.1% as Catholic.
[src:germany/germany-p01] A study, based primarily on church membership rolls, estimated that in 2025 48.1% of the population are not members of any religious organisation or denomination and 46.3% are Christians.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Irreligion in Germany is strongest in major metropolitan areas and throughout the former East Germany.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Islam is the second-largest religion in the country.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In the 2011 census, 1.9% of respondents (1.52 million people) gave their religion as Islam, but this figure is deemed unreliable because a disproportionate number of adherents of this faith (and other religions, such as Judaism) are likely to have made use of their right not to answer the question.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2019, there were an estimated 5.3–5.6 million Muslims with a migrant background (6.4–6.7% of the population), in addition to an unknown number of Muslims without a migrant background.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Most of the Muslims are Sunnis and Alevis from Turkey, but there are a small number of Shi'ites, Ahmadiyyas and other denominations.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Other religions each comprise less than one percent of Germany's population.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2011, formal members of the Jewish community represented no more than 0.2% of the total German population, and 60% of them resided in Berlin.
[src:germany/germany-p01] An estimated 80 to 90 percent of these Jews in Germany are Russian-speaking immigrants from the former Soviet Union who came to Germany from the 1980s onwards.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Responsibility for educational supervision in Germany is primarily organised within the individual states.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Optional kindergarten education is provided for all children between three and six years old, after which school attendance is compulsory for at least nine years depending on the state.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Primary education usually lasts for four to six years.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Secondary schooling is divided into tracks based on whether students pursue academic or vocational education.
[src:germany/germany-p01] A system of apprenticeship called *Duale Ausbildung* leads to a skilled qualification which is almost comparable to an academic degree.
[src:germany/germany-p01] It allows students in vocational training to learn in a company as well as in a state-run trade school.
[src:germany/germany-p01] This model is well regarded and reproduced all around the world.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Most of the German universities are public institutions, and students traditionally study without fee payment.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The general requirement for attending university is the *Abitur*.
[src:germany/germany-p01] According to an OECD report from 2014, Germany is the world's third leading destination for international study.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The established universities in Germany include some of the oldest in the world, with Heidelberg University (established in 1386), Leipzig University (established in 1409) and the University of Rostock (established in 1419) being the oldest in the country.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The Humboldt University of Berlin, founded in 1810 by the liberal educational reformer Wilhelm von Humboldt, became the academic model for many Western universities.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany's system of hospitals, called *Krankenhäuser*, dates from medieval times, and the country has the world's oldest universal health care system, dating from Bismarck's social legislation of the 1880s.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Since the 1880s, reforms and provisions have ensured a balanced health care system.
[src:germany/germany-p01] The population is covered by a health insurance plan provided by statute, with criteria allowing some groups to opt for a private health insurance contract.
[src:germany/germany-p01] According to the World Health Organization (WHO), Germany's health care system was 77% government-funded and 23% privately funded in 2013.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2024, Germany spent 12.27% of its GDP on health care.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany ranked 21st in the world in 2019 in life expectancy with 78.7 years for men and 84.8 years for women according to the WHO, and it had a very low infant mortality rate of 4 deaths per 1,000 live births.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2019, the principal cause of death was cardiovascular disease, at 37%.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Obesity in Germany has been increasingly cited as a major health issue: a 2014 study showed that 52 percent of the adult German population was overweight or obese.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany has an extensive psychiatric care system, with rising demand for mental health services; roughly 27.8% of adults experience a mental disorder annually.
[src:germany/germany-p01] While the system offers comprehensive, insurance-covered care, it faces a shortage of psychotherapists and a pandemic-driven surge in anxiety and depression.
[src:germany/germany-p01] In 2023, 37.7% of adults rated their mental health as excellent or very good.
[src:germany/germany-p01] Germany had the third-highest rate of chronic depression among EU countries in 2019.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Culture in German states has been shaped by major intellectual and popular currents in Europe, both religious and secular, and German scientists, writers and philosophers have played a significant role in the development of Western thought.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Global opinion polls from the BBC revealed that Germany is recognised for having the most positive influence in the world in 2013 and 2014.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Germany is well known for such folk festivals as the Oktoberfest and Christmas customs, which include Advent wreaths, Christmas pageants, Christmas trees, Stollen cakes, and other practices.
[src:germany/germany-p02] As of 2025, UNESCO inscribed 55 properties in Germany on the World Heritage List.
[src:germany/germany-p02] There are a number of public holidays in Germany determined by each state; 3 October has been a national day of Germany since 1990, celebrated as the *Tag der Deutschen Einheit* (German Unity Day).
[src:germany/germany-p02] German painters have influenced Western art.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Albrecht Dürer, Hans Holbein the Younger, Matthias Grünewald and Lucas Cranach the Elder were important German artists of the Renaissance, Johann Baptist Zimmermann of the Baroque, Caspar David Friedrich and Carl Spitzweg of Romanticism, Max Liebermann of Impressionism and Max Ernst of Surrealism.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Several German art groups formed in the 20th century; *Die Brücke* (The Bridge) and *Der Blaue Reiter* (The Blue Rider) influenced the development of expressionism in Munich and Berlin.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The New Objectivity arose in response to expressionism during the Weimar Republic.
[src:germany/germany-p02] After World War II, broad trends in German art include neo-expressionism and the New Leipzig School.
[src:germany/germany-p02] German designers became early leaders of modern product design.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The Berlin Fashion Week and the fashion trade fair Bread & Butter are held twice a year.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Architectural contributions from Germany include the Carolingian and Ottonian styles, which were precursors of Romanesque.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Brick Gothic is a distinctive medieval style that evolved in Germany.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Also in Renaissance and Baroque art, regional and typically German elements evolved (e.g.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Vernacular architecture in Germany is often identified by its timber framing (*Fachwerk*) traditions and varies across regions, and among carpentry styles.
[src:germany/germany-p02] When industrialisation spread across Europe, classicism and a distinctive style of historicism developed in Germany, sometimes referred to as *Gründerzeit* *style*.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Expressionist architecture developed in the 1910s in Germany and influenced Art Deco and other modern styles.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Germany was particularly important in the early modernist movement: it is the home of Werkbund initiated by Hermann Muthesius (New Objectivity), and of the Bauhaus movement founded by Walter Gropius.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Ludwig Mies van der Rohe became one of the world's most renowned architects in the second half of the 20th century; he conceived of the glass façade skyscraper.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Renowned contemporary German architects and offices include Pritzker Prize winners Gottfried Böhm and Frei Otto.
[src:germany/germany-p02] German literature can be traced back to the Middle Ages and the works of writers such as Walther von der Vogelweide and Wolfram von Eschenbach.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Well-known German authors include Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, Friedrich Schiller, Gotthold Ephraim Lessing and Theodor Fontane.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The collections of folk tales published by the Brothers Grimm popularised German folklore on an international level.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The Grimms also gathered and codified regional variants of the German language, grounding their work in historical principles; their *Deutsches Wörterbuch*, or German Dictionary, sometimes called the Grimm dictionary, was begun in 1838 and the first volumes published in 1854.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Influential authors of the 20th century include Gerhart Hauptmann, Thomas Mann, Hermann Hesse, Heinrich Böll, and Günter Grass.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The German book market is the third-largest in the world, after the United States and China.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The Frankfurt Book Fair is the most important in the world for international deals and trading, with a tradition spanning over 500 years.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The Leipzig Book Fair also retains a major position in Europe.
[src:germany/germany-p02] German classical music includes works by some of the world's most well-known composers.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Dieterich Buxtehude, Johann Sebastian Bach and Georg Friedrich Händel were influential composers of the Baroque period.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Ludwig van Beethoven was a crucial figure in the transition between the Classical and Romantic eras.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Carl Maria von Weber, Felix Mendelssohn, Robert Schumann and Johannes Brahms were significant Romantic composers.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Richard Wagner was known for his operas.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Richard Strauss was a leading composer of the late Romantic and early modern eras.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Karlheinz Stockhausen and Wolfgang Rihm are important composers of the 20th and early 21st centuries.
[src:germany/germany-p02] In 2013, Germany was the second-largest music market in Europe, and fourth-largest in the world.
[src:germany/germany-p02] German popular music of the 20th and 21st centuries includes the movements of Neue Deutsche Welle, pop, Ostrock, heavy metal/rock, punk, pop rock, indie, Volksmusik (folk music), schlager pop and German hip hop.
[src:germany/germany-p02] German electronic music gained global influence, with Kraftwerk and Tangerine Dream pioneering in this genre.
[src:germany/germany-p02] DJs and artists of the techno and house music scenes of Germany have become well known (e.g.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Paul van Dyk, Felix Jaehn, Paul Kalkbrenner, Robin Schulz and Scooter).
[src:germany/germany-p02] The largest internationally operating media companies in Germany are Bertelsmann, Axel Springer SE and ProSiebenSat.1 Media.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Germany's television market is the largest in Europe, with over 38 million TV households as of 2012.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Around 90% of German households have cable or satellite TV, with a variety of free-to-view public and commercial channels.
[src:germany/germany-p02] There are more than 300 public and private radio stations in Germany; Germany's national radio network is the Deutschlandradio, while the public Deutsche Welle is the main radio and television broadcaster in foreign languages.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Germany's print media market is the largest in Europe.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The German newspapers with the highest circulation are *Bild*, *Süddeutsche Zeitung*, *Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung* and *Die Welt*.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The largest German magazines include *ADAC Motorwelt* and *Der Spiegel*.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Germany has a large video gaming market, with over 34 million players nationwide.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The annual Gamescom held in Cologne is the world's largest gaming convention.
[src:germany/germany-p02] German cinema has made major technical and artistic contributions to film.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The first works of the Skladanowsky Brothers were shown to an audience in 1895.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The renowned Babelsberg Studio in Potsdam was established in 1912, thus being the first large-scale film studio in the world.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Early German cinema was particularly influential with German expressionists such as Robert Wiene and Friedrich Wilhelm Murnau.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Director Fritz Lang's *Metropolis* (1927) is referred to as the first major science-fiction film.
[src:germany/germany-p02] After 1945, many of the films of the immediate post-war period can be characterised as *Trümmerfilm* (rubble film).
[src:germany/germany-p02] East German film was dominated by the state-owned film studio DEFA, while the dominant genre in West Germany was the *Heimatfilm* ("homeland film").
[src:germany/germany-p02] The Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film ("Oscar") went to the German production *The Tin Drum* (*Die Blechtrommel*) in 1979, to *Nowhere in Africa* (*Nirgendwo in Afrika*) in 2002, and to *The Lives of Others* (*Das Leben der Anderen*) in 2007.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Various Germans won an Oscar for their performances in films.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The annual European Film Awards ceremony is held every other year in Berlin, home of the European Film Academy.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The Berlin International Film Festival known as "Berlinale", awarding the "Golden Bear" and held annually since 1951, is one of the world's leading film festivals.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The "Lolas" are annually awarded in Berlin, at the German Film Awards.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Bread is a significant part of German cuisine, with German bakeries producing about 600 main types of bread and 1,200 types of pastries and rolls (*Brötchen*).
[src:germany/germany-p02] German cheeses account for about 22% of all cheese produced in Europe.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Germans produce their ubiquitous sausages in almost 1,500 varieties, including Bratwurst and Weißwurst.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Germany's beer consumption per capita stood at 110 litres (24 imp gal; 29 US gal) in 2013 and remains among the highest in the world.
[src:germany/germany-p02] German beer purity regulations date back to the 16th century.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Wine has become popular in many parts of the country, especially near the German wine regions.
[src:germany/germany-p02] In 2019, Germany was the ninth-largest wine producer in the world.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The 2018 *Michelin Guide* awarded eleven restaurants in Germany three stars, giving the country a cumulative total of 300 stars.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Football is the most popular sport in Germany.
[src:germany/germany-p02] With more than 7 million official members, the German Football Association (*Deutscher Fußball-Bund*) is the largest single-sport organisation worldwide, and the German top league, the Bundesliga, attracts the second-highest average attendance of all professional sports leagues in the world.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The German men's national football team won the FIFA World Cup in 1954, 1974, 1990, and 2014, the UEFA European Championship in 1972, 1980 and 1996, and the FIFA Confederations Cup in 2017.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Germany is one of the world's leading motor sports countries, with constructors such as BMW and Mercedes playing prominent roles in international competition.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Porsche has won the 24 Hours of Le Mans race 19 times, and Audi 13 times, as of April 2024.
[src:germany/germany-p02] The driver Michael Schumacher has set many motor sport records, having won seven Formula One World Drivers' Championships.
[src:germany/germany-p02] Sebastian Vettel is also among the most successful Formula One drivers of all time.
[src:germany/germany-p02] German athletes historically have been successful contenders in the Olympic Games, ranking third in an all-time Olympic Games medal count when combining East and West German medals prior to German reunification.
[src:germany/germany-p02] In 1936, Berlin hosted the Summer Games and the Winter Games in Garmisch-Partenkirchen.
